1
00:00:00,051 --> 00:00:00,112
you

2
00:00:57,002 --> 00:00:59,585
[SPEAKER_10]: Annyeonghaseyo!

3
00:00:59,825 --> 00:01:00,906
[SPEAKER_10]: How are we all?

4
00:01:00,926 --> 00:01:14,279
[SPEAKER_10]: It's great to see you, Your Excellencies, distinguished guests, members of the media, and importantly, our youth representatives who are here today.

5
00:01:14,780 --> 00:01:20,545
[SPEAKER_10]: Welcome to the 21st Jeju Forum for Peace and Prosperity.

6
00:01:25,667 --> 00:01:34,052
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm Sharon Jeet Lail and it is a genuine pleasure for me to be here on Jeju Island, the island of peace.

7
00:01:34,753 --> 00:01:42,738
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm also delighted to say that we are broadcasting live on Arirang TV and on the Jeju forums YouTube channel.

8
00:01:43,638 --> 00:01:52,586
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, over the next 90 minutes, we are going to be asking the question that's impacting, of course, the global community.

9
00:01:52,906 --> 00:02:00,012
[SPEAKER_10]: And that is, how do we reimagine multilateralism in a rapidly changing world?

10
00:02:00,753 --> 00:02:09,983
[SPEAKER_10]: And we'll be asking that question to the women and men who are seeking to become the next Secretary General of the United Nations.

11
00:02:10,363 --> 00:02:17,130
[SPEAKER_10]: They will be only the tenth leader of that organization to succeed, of course, Antonio Guterres in 2027.

12
00:02:19,205 --> 00:02:30,503
[SPEAKER_10]: But first, let me introduce our favorite son of South Korea, the eighth Secretary General of the United Nations, His Excellency Ban Ki-moon.

13
00:02:31,043 --> 00:02:32,866
[SPEAKER_10]: Excellency, the floor is yours.

14
00:03:00,477 --> 00:03:13,982
[SPEAKER_13]: Excellencies, distinguished guests, ladies and gentlemen, and distinguished candidates for the next Secretary General of the United Nations, welcome to you all.

15
00:03:15,683 --> 00:03:26,267
[SPEAKER_13]: As former Secretary General of the United Nations, it is my distinct honor to welcome you all to Jeju, the island of peace.

16
00:03:27,690 --> 00:03:33,632
[SPEAKER_13]: It is truly moving to witness such a gathering of visionary leaders.

17
00:03:34,872 --> 00:03:41,875
[SPEAKER_13]: I feel the passion that fuels your commitment to our collective future.

18
00:03:43,075 --> 00:03:51,918
[SPEAKER_13]: And it is my firm belief that each of you is ready to shoulder the hopes of humanity.

19
00:03:53,478 --> 00:03:54,679
[SPEAKER_13]: Distinguished candidates,

20
00:03:55,746 --> 00:04:03,988
[SPEAKER_13]: Let me begin with a candid reflection from one who has walked this path before.

21
00:04:05,048 --> 00:04:07,529
[SPEAKER_13]: To be honest, I don't envy you.

22
00:04:10,730 --> 00:04:19,752
[SPEAKER_13]: When I was campaigning for the Office of the Secretary General back in 2006, there was no such forum as this.

23
00:04:20,954 --> 00:04:31,138
[SPEAKER_13]: no public stage where candidates could transparently present and contest their visions before the world's people.

24
00:04:32,358 --> 00:04:42,662
[SPEAKER_13]: In that sense, I was fortunate, but I feel for you this is a very rigorous and demanding process.

25
00:04:43,102 --> 00:04:44,463
[SPEAKER_13]: Be ready for that.

26
00:04:45,563 --> 00:04:50,165
[SPEAKER_13]: And yet, in the same breath, I truly envy you.

27
00:04:51,694 --> 00:05:03,042
[SPEAKER_13]: In my time, I had to seek out every opportunity, moving from capital to capital, often in the shadow of quiet diplomacy.

28
00:05:04,243 --> 00:05:20,115
[SPEAKER_13]: You, however, stand here on the global stage of the Jeju Forum, where you can articulate your vision with transparency and rigor before the world.

29
00:05:22,005 --> 00:05:35,077
[SPEAKER_13]: That openness, the opportunity to be tested on your merits in the clear light of day is a privilege I find genuinely precious.

30
00:05:36,618 --> 00:05:44,445
[SPEAKER_13]: Dear candidates, people often speak of the Secretary General of the United Nations as

31
00:05:45,593 --> 00:05:49,996
[SPEAKER_13]: the quote, present of the world, but I don't agree with this.

32
00:05:50,897 --> 00:05:54,599
[SPEAKER_13]: Or the secular pope, I don't agree with this either.

33
00:05:55,059 --> 00:06:02,945
[SPEAKER_13]: But this is what people would say, have been saying about the post of the Secretary General of the United Nations.

34
00:06:03,807 --> 00:06:21,214
[SPEAKER_13]: But those who have held this position before, including myself, told now, tell the truth that S.G., which is Secretary General, is often

35
00:06:22,417 --> 00:06:28,278
[SPEAKER_13]: in reality, quoted as the scapegoat, scapegoat.

36
00:06:29,038 --> 00:06:35,680
[SPEAKER_13]: SUGs are often called scapegoat, so you should be ready to become a scapegoat.

37
00:06:37,180 --> 00:06:48,302
[SPEAKER_13]: The position demands an immense weight of responsibility, endless reserve of patience, and at times, profound sense of solitude.

38
00:06:49,420 --> 00:07:07,225
[SPEAKER_13]: And yet, I envy you because one of you will work side by side with the most dedicated people on Earth, UN staff who have pledged their lives to the cause of humanity.

39
00:07:08,906 --> 00:07:17,168
[SPEAKER_13]: You will share burdens in the most difficult corners of the globe, and in doing so,

40
00:07:18,770 --> 00:07:26,635
[SPEAKER_13]: forged bonds of fellowship that no title or salary can ever replicate.

41
00:07:27,676 --> 00:07:42,126
[SPEAKER_13]: You will also be supported by the diplomats, business leaders, and civil society organizations who are eager to unite behind your leadership and shape the course of history.

42
00:07:44,047 --> 00:07:47,550
[SPEAKER_13]: Excellencies, ladies and gentlemen, dear colleagues,

43
00:07:48,773 --> 00:07:51,395
[SPEAKER_13]: I know all the candidates personally.

44
00:07:51,695 --> 00:07:55,418
[SPEAKER_13]: I have known all of you in person, in fact, without fail.

45
00:07:56,639 --> 00:08:15,214
[SPEAKER_13]: Having worked alongside them for years, I can attest that whoever is elected tomorrow, he or she is fully capable of assuming this post office with distinction.

46
00:08:17,299 --> 00:08:25,044
[SPEAKER_13]: Looking at the road ahead, I must confess again, I do not envy you.

47
00:08:25,345 --> 00:08:27,546
[SPEAKER_13]: Again, this is what I'm telling you.

48
00:08:29,207 --> 00:08:44,738
[SPEAKER_13]: Whoever assume the office of the Secretary General of the United Nations on January 1st next year will inherit an institution facing lot of challenges of truly historic proportions.

49
00:08:45,808 --> 00:09:00,792
[SPEAKER_13]: The United Nations is in the grips of a serious financial crisis, its authority questioned, and its credibility strained by relentless calls for reform.

50
00:09:02,132 --> 00:09:10,935
[SPEAKER_13]: The war in Ukraine has entered its fifth year with no clear prospect for a peaceful resolution.

51
00:09:11,675 --> 00:09:15,156
[SPEAKER_13]: At the same time, the conflict in the Middle East

52
00:09:16,469 --> 00:09:21,151
[SPEAKER_13]: more seriously the war between the United States and Iran.

53
00:09:22,492 --> 00:09:41,440
[SPEAKER_13]: Though the parties have signed the peace agreement, continue to inflict a profound human and economic and geopolitical cost, devastating consequences for the countries involved and the wider world.

54
00:09:43,004 --> 00:09:54,269
[SPEAKER_13]: On the other hand, the climate crisis grows more urgently with every passing year, maybe every passing second or hour.

55
00:09:55,410 --> 00:10:09,997
[SPEAKER_13]: And now, artificial intelligence, AI, introduces a new dimension of uncertainty that our existing international frameworks are wholly unprepared to address.

56
00:10:11,294 --> 00:10:20,846
[SPEAKER_13]: But there is another side to this, the potential for you to write an epic chapter in the history of the United Nations.

57
00:10:21,867 --> 00:10:25,712
[SPEAKER_13]: In this regard, the next Secretary General of the United Nations

58
00:10:26,488 --> 00:10:51,069
[SPEAKER_13]: will have the rare privilege of rebuilding shattered trust in multilateralism and demonstrating convincingly and concretely that the United Nations can still make a real tangible difference in the lives of ordinary people everywhere in this world.

59
00:10:52,141 --> 00:10:57,764
[SPEAKER_13]: you will serve as the true architect of the global agenda.

60
00:11:00,046 --> 00:11:08,170
[SPEAKER_13]: I still remember the moments during my own tenure that filled me with the deepest sense of purpose.

61
00:11:09,171 --> 00:11:21,418
[SPEAKER_13]: The day the Paris Climate Change Agreement was adopted, the day the 17 goals of sustainable development goals were adopted and endorsed,

62
00:11:22,542 --> 00:11:32,251
[SPEAKER_13]: unanimously by 193 member nations, and the day when the UN Women was established.

63
00:11:33,753 --> 00:11:40,800
[SPEAKER_13]: Those were the days when all the UN member states were united as one.

64
00:11:41,420 --> 00:11:45,784
[SPEAKER_13]: I am proud to have worked with a member state and

65
00:11:46,692 --> 00:11:48,893
[SPEAKER_13]: diligently working UN staff.

66
00:11:49,673 --> 00:11:54,534
[SPEAKER_13]: You will continue to carry on these initiatives.

67
00:11:55,354 --> 00:12:11,518
[SPEAKER_13]: The profound realization that the single collective decision could set a positive course for billions of lives, the sense of meaning is a reward I know you too will come to cherish.

68
00:12:13,228 --> 00:12:20,752
[SPEAKER_13]: for you will be the ones to ignite the hope when the world needs it most.

69
00:12:21,412 --> 00:12:27,856
[SPEAKER_13]: In that regard, I envy you more than anyone else, so you should be ready for that.

70
00:12:29,116 --> 00:12:41,203
[SPEAKER_13]: Excellencies, Distinguished Foreign Minister Cho Hyun of Republic of Korea, dear candidates for the next UN Secretary General, ladies and gentlemen,

71
00:12:42,550 --> 00:12:53,120
[SPEAKER_13]: I myself was a child of war who, with the help of the United Nations, rose to become a man of peace.

72
00:12:54,361 --> 00:13:06,032
[SPEAKER_13]: The Republic of Korea rose from the ashes of the Korean War of 1950 with the vital support of the United Nations and its member states.

73
00:13:07,222 --> 00:13:12,830
[SPEAKER_13]: having transformed from an aid recipient into donor nations.

74
00:13:13,310 --> 00:13:21,662
[SPEAKER_13]: Korea is, whether you believe it or not, Korea is the only country in the world accepting all those

75
00:13:22,902 --> 00:13:31,286
[SPEAKER_13]: regular members of OECD, that is the only country who has turned from donor receiving to donor giving country.

76
00:13:31,886 --> 00:13:42,291
[SPEAKER_13]: So it's not only the Korean people, there are many developing countries who are really working hard to overcome their difficulties.

77
00:13:42,971 --> 00:13:49,394
[SPEAKER_13]: I think Korea can show the examples to become a donor giving country.

78
00:13:50,243 --> 00:13:52,785
[SPEAKER_13]: that we are very much proud of that.

79
00:13:53,866 --> 00:14:03,413
[SPEAKER_13]: Korea now understands the value of multilateral diplomacy perhaps more deeply than any other one else.

80
00:14:04,554 --> 00:14:12,620
[SPEAKER_13]: Korea will remain your most steadfast partner as you embark on this bold journey.

81
00:14:13,581 --> 00:14:17,424
[SPEAKER_13]: And I personally will always be in your corner.

82
00:14:18,613 --> 00:14:32,341
[SPEAKER_13]: I sincerely hope that the conversation to be held here in Jeju right now will serve as a guiding compass for the next Secretary General and for all harmony.

83
00:14:33,402 --> 00:14:38,705
[SPEAKER_13]: To each of the proud candidates, again, I don't envy you.

84
00:14:39,125 --> 00:14:41,887
[SPEAKER_13]: I don't know why I repeat this message to you.

85
00:14:43,463 --> 00:14:48,025
[SPEAKER_13]: because you may soon be frustrated from day two.

86
00:14:48,345 --> 00:14:49,825
[SPEAKER_13]: Day one, you will be very happy.

87
00:14:50,165 --> 00:14:52,446
[SPEAKER_13]: Day two, be prepared for that.

88
00:14:53,606 --> 00:14:56,187
[SPEAKER_13]: And yet, again, I envy you.

89
00:14:56,808 --> 00:14:57,388
[SPEAKER_13]: I envy you.

90
00:14:57,708 --> 00:15:00,929
[SPEAKER_13]: I give you my full support, full, you know, support.

91
00:15:01,449 --> 00:15:06,771
[SPEAKER_13]: I wish you courage, clarity of vision, and great succession.

92
00:15:07,331 --> 00:15:08,331
[SPEAKER_13]: It's very important.

93
00:15:08,391 --> 00:15:09,992
[SPEAKER_13]: You are already global citizens.

94
00:15:10,899 --> 00:15:15,221
[SPEAKER_13]: with global vision, global season, act like a global season.

95
00:15:15,861 --> 00:15:18,923
[SPEAKER_13]: Again, ladies and gentlemen, thank you very much.

96
00:15:20,063 --> 00:15:21,764
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you very much.

97
00:15:21,784 --> 00:15:22,364
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

98
00:15:23,084 --> 00:15:25,005
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you very much.

99
00:15:25,045 --> 00:15:25,385
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

100
00:15:25,405 --> 00:15:26,946
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

101
00:15:37,031 --> 00:15:39,392
[SPEAKER_10]: And what excellent advice.

102
00:15:39,672 --> 00:15:52,116
[SPEAKER_10]: And of course, as a true son of Korea and one of the most respected voices in global diplomacy, we are so grateful for your presence here today, of course, Secretary General Ban Ki-moon.

103
00:15:52,636 --> 00:16:01,940
[SPEAKER_10]: And next up, it is my pleasure to invite the Foreign Minister of the Republic of Korea, His Excellency Cho Hyun, to deliver his remarks.

104
00:16:02,460 --> 00:16:03,100
[SPEAKER_10]: Minister, please.

105
00:16:15,325 --> 00:16:18,106
[SPEAKER_12]: Good afternoon, ladies and gentlemen, excellencies.

106
00:16:19,647 --> 00:16:27,892
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, it is an honor to address this distinguished people here in Jeju.

107
00:16:28,592 --> 00:16:38,397
[SPEAKER_12]: Looking at the candidates gathered here, I cannot help but feel a profound sense of deja vu.

108
00:16:38,998 --> 00:16:41,219
[SPEAKER_12]: Although Secretary General Pan

109
00:16:42,517 --> 00:16:47,841
[SPEAKER_12]: said that there had been no such beauty contest at the time, at his time.

110
00:16:48,381 --> 00:16:49,202
[SPEAKER_12]: There was one.

111
00:16:51,744 --> 00:16:54,946
[SPEAKER_12]: So it takes me to 20 years ago.

112
00:16:55,607 --> 00:17:05,494
[SPEAKER_12]: I was accompanying then Foreign Minister Pan to Davos, the first and the only beauty contest held in Davos.

113
00:17:07,015 --> 00:17:11,138
[SPEAKER_12]: And at the airport, when I had a chance,

114
00:17:12,415 --> 00:17:16,260
[SPEAKER_12]: I said to him an unsolicited advice.

115
00:17:17,541 --> 00:17:28,073
[SPEAKER_12]: Minister, whichever questions I address to you, make your answer short, sweet, and simple.

116
00:17:29,694 --> 00:17:32,738
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, despite my advice,

117
00:17:34,357 --> 00:17:39,479
[SPEAKER_12]: He gave enough long, sophisticated, eloquent answers.

118
00:17:40,619 --> 00:17:42,400
[SPEAKER_12]: And the rest is history.

119
00:17:45,160 --> 00:17:48,722
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, so I talked to the candidates.

120
00:17:49,682 --> 00:17:58,665
[SPEAKER_12]: Speak up and show your true colors, as did Secretary General Ban Ki-moon 20 some years ago.

121
00:18:00,325 --> 00:18:01,626
[SPEAKER_12]: On a serious note,

122
00:18:02,815 --> 00:18:09,619
[SPEAKER_12]: I am compelled to compare the challenges of the time and now.

123
00:18:10,960 --> 00:18:18,605
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, we had war in the Middle East.

124
00:18:18,685 --> 00:18:22,307
[SPEAKER_12]: The war in Iraq just finished at the time.

125
00:18:22,928 --> 00:18:30,593
[SPEAKER_12]: Now we have the war in Iran at the critical inflection point.

126
00:18:32,403 --> 00:18:36,564
[SPEAKER_12]: Back then, the civil war in Darfur just finished.

127
00:18:36,864 --> 00:18:42,725
[SPEAKER_12]: Now, today, Sudan continues to be raged by internal war.

128
00:18:44,026 --> 00:18:52,047
[SPEAKER_12]: 20 years ago, achieving MDGs felt so ambitious, too ambitious.

129
00:18:53,668 --> 00:18:59,249
[SPEAKER_12]: Today, achieving SDG seems to be ever more elusive.

130
00:19:01,465 --> 00:19:15,437
[SPEAKER_12]: In that respect, I think we have been fragmented, unlike the catchphrasing word of reinventing the fragmented world.

131
00:19:16,578 --> 00:19:18,659
[SPEAKER_12]: So what is to be done?

132
00:19:20,201 --> 00:19:22,603
[SPEAKER_12]: The only big difference is that

133
00:19:24,010 --> 00:19:31,837
[SPEAKER_12]: The United Nations today has become more and more invisible, less and less visible.

134
00:19:32,357 --> 00:19:41,765
[SPEAKER_12]: So it should be the job of the next Secretary General to make it visible and lead the world.

135
00:19:43,026 --> 00:19:51,433
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, in several months' time, one of the five candidates will emerge, the Secretary General of the United Nations.

136
00:19:53,764 --> 00:20:01,327
[SPEAKER_12]: She or he will jump into the cockpit of the world plane.

137
00:20:03,008 --> 00:20:17,715
[SPEAKER_12]: And I think all of you are qualified, but whoever climbs the rudder to the cockpit will say to the rest of the world,

138
00:20:19,185 --> 00:20:24,407
[SPEAKER_12]: to go through this turbulence, fasten your seatbelt.

139
00:20:26,387 --> 00:20:43,253
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, since this will be the most unenviable job, as said by Secretary General Ban Ki-moon, we all owe our thanks to you for your courage in stepping up.

140
00:20:43,273 --> 00:20:45,954
[SPEAKER_12]: I look forward to hearing from you.

141
00:20:46,394 --> 00:20:47,114
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you very much.

142
00:20:52,382 --> 00:20:54,623
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you so much, Minister Cho.

143
00:20:55,284 --> 00:20:58,985
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, some brave candidates indeed, as we've been hearing.

144
00:20:59,726 --> 00:21:10,551
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, we're going to move on to our candidates who are vying to become a Secretary General, but one of them couldn't be with us here today, and that is Michelle Bachelet.

145
00:21:10,631 --> 00:21:13,753
[SPEAKER_10]: She has kindly sent us a video message instead.

146
00:21:14,093 --> 00:21:19,656
[SPEAKER_10]: She is, of course, the former President of Chile and the former United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights.

147
00:21:19,996 --> 00:21:21,157
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's hear her message.

148
00:21:22,665 --> 00:21:29,029
[BACHELET]: Excellencies, dear friends, I deeply regret not being able to join you in person today.

149
00:21:29,709 --> 00:21:31,670
[BACHELET]: A scheduling conflict made it impossible.

150
00:21:32,191 --> 00:21:47,360
[BACHELET]: I hope we will have new opportunities to talk about peace and youth soon, but I did not want to miss this moment because what you are discussing matters enormously and it connects directly to why I am running for Secretary General.

151
00:21:49,138 --> 00:21:58,346
[BACHELET]: The United Nations was built on a simple but radical idea that nations, however different, can choose cooperation over confrontation.

152
00:21:58,926 --> 00:22:06,092
[BACHELET]: That idea is under pressure today, but I have spent my life proving that dialogue can achieve what force never will.

153
00:22:06,853 --> 00:22:15,220
[BACHELET]: Multilateralism is dialogue in practice, and building consensus, even when it seems impossible, is what I have done my entire life.

154
00:22:15,820 --> 00:22:22,484
[BACHELET]: as president of Chile twice, as founding executive director of the UN Women, and as high commissioner for human rights.

155
00:22:24,145 --> 00:22:26,967
[BACHELET]: The question is not whether we need multilateralism.

156
00:22:27,287 --> 00:22:28,828
[BACHELET]: The question is what kind?

157
00:22:29,749 --> 00:22:42,717
[BACHELET]: One that prevents crisis before they explode, one that amplifies the voices of all the member states of the UN, and one that is firmly anchored in the principles and values of the UN Charter.

158
00:22:43,877 --> 00:22:56,729
[BACHELET]: Strengthening that cooperation requires a secretary general who knows when to facilitate, who can build the room where agreement becomes possible, hold the channel open when parties refuse to speak.

159
00:22:57,489 --> 00:23:01,833
[BACHELET]: That requires patience, discretion, and the trust of all sides.

160
00:23:02,494 --> 00:23:09,220
[BACHELET]: And that trust must include everyone at the table, especially those who have been kept out of the room for too long.

161
00:23:09,945 --> 00:23:12,267
[BACHELET]: Young people, above all, you know your communities.

162
00:23:12,347 --> 00:23:15,409
[BACHELET]: You see what is happening on the ground.

163
00:23:15,789 --> 00:23:19,211
[BACHELET]: You have ideas, energy, and a profound stake in getting this right.

164
00:23:20,072 --> 00:23:24,635
[BACHELET]: We already have Resolution 2250 on youth, peace, and security.

165
00:23:25,015 --> 00:23:28,417
[BACHELET]: We need to implement it and apply the same logic everywhere.

166
00:23:29,058 --> 00:23:35,362
[BACHELET]: Young people must be at the table, not as observers, but as co-authors of the decisions that shape our world.

167
00:23:36,142 --> 00:23:42,905
[BACHELET]: I also believe we cannot have peace without development, and we cannot have peace without human rights.

168
00:23:43,565 --> 00:23:53,730
[BACHELET]: These three pillars must be treated as one, because much of what we call inevitable conflict, displacement, suffering, was actually preventable.

169
00:23:54,650 --> 00:23:59,732
[BACHELET]: Prevention requires presence, investment, and the courage to act early.

170
00:24:01,153 --> 00:24:09,066
[BACHELET]: That is why I offer experience, commitment and the deep conviction that the multilateralism, when it works, changes lives.

171
00:24:10,028 --> 00:24:14,595
[BACHELET]: I look forward to continuing this conversation with you in person very soon.

172
00:24:15,436 --> 00:24:15,797
[BACHELET]: Thank you.

173
00:24:20,723 --> 00:24:23,525
[SPEAKER_10]: Madame Bachelet, thank you very much for that message.

174
00:24:23,545 --> 00:24:32,791
[SPEAKER_10]: And now, please allow me to welcome our very brave candidates who are vying to become the next Secretary General of the United Nations.

175
00:24:33,251 --> 00:24:36,173
[SPEAKER_10]: And they will join us on stage in alphabetical order.

176
00:24:36,653 --> 00:24:44,719
[SPEAKER_10]: So, let me invite Maria Fernanda Espinosa, former President of the UN General Assembly, and Ecuador's former Foreign Minister.

177
00:24:44,819 --> 00:24:46,420
[SPEAKER_10]: Please join us on stage.

178
00:24:51,290 --> 00:24:57,295
[SPEAKER_10]: We also have Rafael Grossi, the Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency.

179
00:24:58,435 --> 00:24:59,636
[SPEAKER_10]: Come and join us, please, sir.

