203
00:27:21,370 --> 00:27:28,480
[SPEAKER_10]: What is the one experience you've had here in Jeju that has particularly stayed with you?

204
00:27:28,860 --> 00:27:31,364
[SPEAKER_10]: And you have one minute for this question.

205
00:27:31,384 --> 00:27:36,631
[SPEAKER_10]: This is just testing your timekeeping to begin with, but one minute for this one, and later you'll have two minutes.

206
00:27:36,651 --> 00:27:37,652
[SPEAKER_10]: So let's start with you, Maria.

207
00:27:38,153 --> 00:27:38,934
[ESPINOSA]: Well, thank you.

208
00:27:39,014 --> 00:27:40,435
[ESPINOSA]: Thank you to the organizers.

209
00:27:40,615 --> 00:27:47,000
[ESPINOSA]: And I have to say, yes, my heart beating because of the beauty of the place, because of the kindness of its people.

210
00:27:47,400 --> 00:27:57,068
[ESPINOSA]: But I have to say one thing that I have kept deep in my heart is the Xenial women.

211
00:27:57,989 --> 00:28:05,395
[ESPINOSA]: These are women from this island that go down deep in the sea to harvest seafood.

212
00:28:06,297 --> 00:28:13,821
[ESPINOSA]: And they can be in the water for more than 10 minutes without an oxygen tank.

213
00:28:14,502 --> 00:28:15,803
[ESPINOSA]: This is unbelievable.

214
00:28:15,923 --> 00:28:27,970
[ESPINOSA]: And it shows the knowledge, the wisdom, the resilience, the quiet leadership that I see and recognize very much in the soul of the Korean people.

215
00:28:28,410 --> 00:28:35,354
[ESPINOSA]: So kudos for the Haneul women that have shown endurance, resilience,

216
00:28:35,795 --> 00:28:36,676
[ESPINOSA]: in deep knowledge.

217
00:28:36,816 --> 00:28:37,797
[ESPINOSA]: I'm touched by that.

218
00:28:38,759 --> 00:28:39,299
[ESPINOSA]: Fantastic.

219
00:28:39,319 --> 00:28:40,921
[SPEAKER_10]: You've kept to your minute, Rafael.

220
00:28:43,264 --> 00:28:43,805
[GROSSI]: Thank you very much.

221
00:28:43,925 --> 00:28:44,646
[GROSSI]: Great to be here.

222
00:28:45,827 --> 00:28:55,859
[GROSSI]: Indeed, we know the history, we know what this place represents in good and bad, and the fact that it has become a place that represents peace

223
00:28:57,035 --> 00:28:57,596
[GROSSI]: says it all.

224
00:28:59,356 --> 00:29:06,259
[GROSSI]: But the one thing I was very happy about is that in record time I got an ID.

225
00:29:07,540 --> 00:29:21,506
[GROSSI]: And in these times where welcoming people and protecting people becomes really challenging, that speaks miles about the welcoming attitude

226
00:29:22,390 --> 00:29:29,115
[GROSSI]: And having us for this debate, which we are all looking forward to, is unique.

227
00:29:29,155 --> 00:29:32,497
[GROSSI]: So looking forward to listen to my colleagues and having my pit as well.

228
00:29:32,537 --> 00:29:33,358
[GROSSI]: One minute's up.

229
00:29:33,418 --> 00:29:34,178
[GROSSI]: Fantastic.

230
00:29:34,258 --> 00:29:34,819
[SPEAKER_10]: That's great.

231
00:29:35,099 --> 00:29:35,699
[SPEAKER_10]: Efficiency.

232
00:29:35,739 --> 00:29:36,280
[SPEAKER_10]: We like that.

233
00:29:37,240 --> 00:29:37,581
[SPEAKER_10]: Rebecca.

234
00:29:38,578 --> 00:29:53,106
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, really, yesterday, the children that sang to us and hugged us and remind us of the warmth and the welcoming of the people of Korea, they were so wonderful.

235
00:29:53,947 --> 00:30:05,334
[GRYNSPAN]: And at the same time, looking at that and thinking about these children, wonderful children, you have to remind everybody of why we are here, yes?

236
00:30:05,434 --> 00:30:07,175
[GRYNSPAN]: Because there are many children in the world.

237
00:30:07,815 --> 00:30:17,142
[GRYNSPAN]: that are going through war, through hunger, through health issues and disease.

238
00:30:17,783 --> 00:30:33,635
[GRYNSPAN]: And so let's all come together again to cooperate, to really save all the children of the world, to really make the children that we saw yesterday the norm and not the exception.

239
00:30:34,416 --> 00:30:34,916
[GRYNSPAN]: Wonderful.

240
00:30:34,956 --> 00:30:35,556
[GRYNSPAN]: Thank you.

241
00:30:35,597 --> 00:30:36,117
[GRYNSPAN]: And Carolyn?

242
00:30:36,864 --> 00:30:37,805
[RODRIGUES]: Thank you, Sharon.

243
00:30:38,505 --> 00:30:39,006
[RODRIGUES]: Three things.

244
00:30:39,726 --> 00:30:49,595
[RODRIGUES]: First, it was the stone walls last evening, and between those stone walls there were spaces, and I see that as deltas for progress, even when there is a wall.

245
00:30:50,404 --> 00:30:56,365
[RODRIGUES]: Secondly, the rain, like a sense of renewal yesterday, today.

246
00:30:56,785 --> 00:31:00,466
[RODRIGUES]: And thirdly, the greenery, just beautiful as well.

247
00:31:01,106 --> 00:31:04,767
[RODRIGUES]: Greenery that we would all like to see all over our countries.

248
00:31:04,827 --> 00:31:09,248
[RODRIGUES]: And I come from a country with 80% forest cover, so I was at home.

249
00:31:09,808 --> 00:31:14,109
[RODRIGUES]: And lastly, just the hospitality of the Korean people.

250
00:31:14,289 --> 00:31:17,070
[RODRIGUES]: Thank you.

251
00:31:17,130 --> 00:31:17,650
[RODRIGUES]: Thank you.

252
00:31:17,670 --> 00:31:18,830
[SPEAKER_10]: And finally, Mackie.

253
00:31:19,627 --> 00:31:22,368
[SALL]: Thank you.

254
00:31:22,848 --> 00:31:35,370
[SALL]: Dear Secretary General and the government of Korea, most people come to Jeju and see the beautiful of this island.

255
00:31:36,970 --> 00:31:46,792
[SALL]: As a geologist, I come to Jeju and I see the beautiful volcano, beautiful rocks,

256
00:31:48,431 --> 00:31:59,218
[SALL]: that shows that this island was created by huge and powerful forces below surface.

257
00:32:00,899 --> 00:32:06,122
[SALL]: That's why today we all know Jeju as the land of peace.

258
00:32:08,303 --> 00:32:13,066
[SALL]: That is why I'm honored and very excited to be here with all candidates.

259
00:32:13,858 --> 00:32:18,782
[SALL]: and I congratulate them to talk about what we have together.

260
00:32:19,302 --> 00:32:24,547
[SALL]: This fragmented world, I hope we will have a very dynamic and very positive discussion.

261
00:32:24,807 --> 00:32:25,227
[SALL]: Thank you.

262
00:32:25,527 --> 00:32:26,048
[SPEAKER_10]: Wonderful.

263
00:32:26,128 --> 00:32:29,010
[SPEAKER_10]: So from the perspective of a geologist, how wonderful to hear that.

264
00:32:30,131 --> 00:32:32,713
[SPEAKER_10]: Brilliant, so the first starter question out of the way.

265
00:32:32,873 --> 00:32:50,586
[SPEAKER_10]: This is now where we get to the real gist of the conversation and it is what we've heard this morning as well from Secretary General Ban Ki-moon, the issue of multilateralism being so much under strain and we know that the system globally is fragmented at the moment.

266
00:32:50,646 --> 00:32:53,768
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't need to list it out, there are so many things happening right now.

267
00:32:54,529 --> 00:32:58,872
[SPEAKER_10]: Lots of growing questions about whether existing institutions like the UN

268
00:32:59,392 --> 00:33:00,792
[SPEAKER_10]: are fit for purpose.

269
00:33:00,912 --> 00:33:08,354
[SPEAKER_10]: So alphabetically again, I'm going to start with you Maria, because many people believe of course that the UN system is becoming ineffectual.

270
00:33:08,594 --> 00:33:14,955
[SPEAKER_10]: It's a lot less effective, particularly as divisions between major powers deepen.

271
00:33:15,735 --> 00:33:23,237
[SPEAKER_10]: What do you see as the greatest weakness in today's multilateral system and how do you plan to fix it?

272
00:33:24,157 --> 00:33:24,577
[SPEAKER_10]: Two minutes.

273
00:33:25,432 --> 00:33:26,092
[ESPINOSA]: Well, thank you.

274
00:33:26,132 --> 00:33:30,533
[ESPINOSA]: First of all, I think that we have always experienced division in the world.

275
00:33:31,474 --> 00:33:34,274
[ESPINOSA]: The UN was born out of division.

276
00:33:35,775 --> 00:33:41,036
[ESPINOSA]: I think the context is perhaps different today after 80 years of history.

277
00:33:41,616 --> 00:33:45,037
[ESPINOSA]: And I would like to mention three key words because time is short.

278
00:33:46,058 --> 00:33:49,138
[ESPINOSA]: What are the issues that we need to rebuild and restore?

279
00:33:49,839 --> 00:33:53,600
[ESPINOSA]: Because we're very good at diagnosis and less good at solutions.

280
00:33:54,300 --> 00:33:54,900
[ESPINOSA]: Number one,

281
00:33:56,638 --> 00:33:57,559
[ESPINOSA]: is trust.

282
00:33:58,520 --> 00:34:11,272
[ESPINOSA]: We really need to rebuild trust in the organization, trust among member states, and trust between the secretary general and the secretariat and the member states.

283
00:34:12,053 --> 00:34:23,080
[ESPINOSA]: And this is done if you are perceived, not just say, but just perceived as an impartial, honest broker.

284
00:34:23,941 --> 00:34:35,148
[ESPINOSA]: Impartiality means that you can be legitimate to all, serve all, and bring all the parties together.

285
00:34:36,048 --> 00:34:41,892
[ESPINOSA]: You have to be a Secretary General partial only to the Charter and to international law.

286
00:34:42,352 --> 00:34:45,694
[ESPINOSA]: The second key word is performance.

287
00:34:46,574 --> 00:34:52,238
[ESPINOSA]: I think the UN is experiencing the biggest implementation gap in history.

288
00:34:52,938 --> 00:35:13,143
[ESPINOSA]: the promises that are written in the charter, the commitments we sign, the resolutions we adopt, and yet the people on the ground are not seeing how the UN is improving their daily lives, how they live in a safer environment, how they can look at the future with hope.

289
00:35:13,923 --> 00:35:19,664
[ESPINOSA]: So to close the implementation gap, I would use another key word, accountability.

290
00:35:20,445 --> 00:35:21,405
[ESPINOSA]: Accountability.

291
00:35:22,725 --> 00:35:28,027
[ESPINOSA]: There is the need for a new and renewed accountability infrastructure.

292
00:35:28,407 --> 00:35:34,389
[ESPINOSA]: And the third, my time is up, but at least I would just mention, convene and partner.

293
00:35:35,030 --> 00:35:49,735
[ESPINOSA]: The UN is the beating heart of multilateralism, but has the responsibility and the legitimacy to bring all regions, all actors, banks, the private sector, and of course member states

294
00:35:50,155 --> 00:35:54,017
[ESPINOSA]: together to solve the current challenges of our times.

295
00:35:54,117 --> 00:35:54,698
[SPEAKER_10]: Wonderful.

296
00:35:54,818 --> 00:36:01,542
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for almost meeting your two-minute mark and it's all about trust, performance and convening, which is your three points.

297
00:36:02,242 --> 00:36:10,206
[SPEAKER_10]: Rafael, I'm going to come to you about another issue that came up this morning in the leadership conversation and that is about the smaller groupings.

298
00:36:10,246 --> 00:36:14,469
[SPEAKER_10]: We heard a lot about ASEAN from the former Indonesian president as well as from

299
00:36:15,029 --> 00:36:26,456
[SPEAKER_10]: Secretary General Ban Ki-moon, those smaller groupings such as G20, all the other alliances out there, MIKTO as well we heard about, they are all there to tackle global challenges.

300
00:36:26,496 --> 00:36:32,540
[SPEAKER_10]: So do these arrangements strengthen the UN or do they risk sidelining it?

301
00:36:33,284 --> 00:36:34,305
[GROSSI]: can go both ways.

302
00:36:35,026 --> 00:36:36,828
[GROSSI]: The thing is how we go about it.

303
00:36:37,368 --> 00:36:44,775
[GROSSI]: The existence and the presence of other groupings and then you could of course categorize this in many different ways.

304
00:36:46,057 --> 00:36:50,081
[GROSSI]: You have organizations, institutions that do exist, including within

305
00:36:50,721 --> 00:36:54,823
[GROSSI]: the UN system which did not exist back in 1945.

306
00:36:55,564 --> 00:37:19,738
[GROSSI]: But you have these groupings and often one hears this argument that you are putting across that the UN perhaps is not reflecting the world as it is and why should it when we have the G7 or the G20 or the BRICS or the Shanghai Cooperation Organization or the Organization of Islamic Cooperation and we could continue

307
00:37:20,398 --> 00:37:21,199
[GROSSI]: enumerating them.

308
00:37:22,079 --> 00:37:33,766
[GROSSI]: The existence of these groupings I see as a strength in the sense that they reflect a number of circumstances.

309
00:37:34,667 --> 00:37:42,151
[GROSSI]: In some cases, it's a grouping that came together because of a specific situation, like the G20 after the 2008 crisis.

310
00:37:42,531 --> 00:37:43,852
[GROSSI]: In some other cases, like the

311
00:37:46,493 --> 00:37:48,054
[GROSSI]: before G7.

312
00:37:48,434 --> 00:37:52,936
[GROSSI]: Now it is a political, strategic evolution.

313
00:37:54,076 --> 00:38:03,320
[GROSSI]: BRICS is a reply to the gathering of other types of developed economies.

314
00:38:03,520 --> 00:38:14,445
[GROSSI]: So all of this is there, and through them we can at the UN system or from the UN system get

315
00:38:15,805 --> 00:38:20,628
[GROSSI]: views that are reflecting this particular set of problems.

316
00:38:21,428 --> 00:38:30,693
[GROSSI]: But at the end of the day, at the end of the day, the UN continues to be the only sole global platform.

317
00:38:30,933 --> 00:38:38,576
[GROSSI]: Because all these groupings in all their beauty and effectiveness cannot reflect global preoccupations.

318
00:38:38,756 --> 00:38:39,297
[GROSSI]: They reflect

319
00:38:39,897 --> 00:38:46,523
[GROSSI]: Partial visions and rightly so but this is why we have and we will continue to have the UN

320
00:38:47,437 --> 00:38:48,458
[SPEAKER_10]: Well said, thank you.

321
00:38:49,278 --> 00:38:58,443
[SPEAKER_10]: Rebecca Greenspan, we've heard a lot about issues such as climate change, artificial intelligence as well is a key one, as well as global health.

322
00:38:58,463 --> 00:39:02,205
[SPEAKER_10]: Of course, we've come out of the pandemic a few years ago, we know how that ended.

323
00:39:02,945 --> 00:39:15,391
[SPEAKER_10]: So how should the UN work more closely, and particularly in your role at UNCTAD, you must have done very closely with the private sector, while of course maintaining its independence and legitimacy?

324
00:39:16,492 --> 00:39:28,676
[GRYNSPAN]: Yeah, let me first say that part of the thing with the global challenges is that we can fragment our actions, but we cannot fragment our problems.

325
00:39:29,496 --> 00:39:34,837
[GRYNSPAN]: And that's why we have to get together to be able to solve the problems.

326
00:39:35,358 --> 00:39:39,539
[GRYNSPAN]: When we act alone, we don't solve the problems, we just deepen them.

327
00:39:40,379 --> 00:39:46,264
[GRYNSPAN]: And with respect to the partnering, I really believe that the UN has to change the culture.

328
00:39:47,184 --> 00:39:50,967
[GRYNSPAN]: We think that everything has to happen in the UN.

329
00:39:51,688 --> 00:39:55,611
[GRYNSPAN]: And this 2026 is different than 1945.

330
00:39:57,372 --> 00:39:59,794
[GRYNSPAN]: In a good sense, too.

331
00:39:59,934 --> 00:40:03,638
[GRYNSPAN]: In 1945, maybe, all the capacities were in the UN.

332
00:40:04,258 --> 00:40:06,880
[GRYNSPAN]: But today, countries have more capacities.

333
00:40:07,241 --> 00:40:10,624
[GRYNSPAN]: There are new regional organizations that have capacities.

334
00:40:10,984 --> 00:40:14,767
[GRYNSPAN]: The private sector and the civil society has more capacities.

335
00:40:15,188 --> 00:40:18,150
[GRYNSPAN]: So we have to learn to partner.

336
00:40:18,891 --> 00:40:23,295
[GRYNSPAN]: As I say, the UN is unique, but it's not alone.

337
00:40:24,360 --> 00:40:45,604
[GRYNSPAN]: So we need to include the private sector in the conversation, especially, for example, in the frontier of knowledge and the frontier of technology for responsible AI and to close the gaps in the digital space to be able to face global health and the global challenges.

338
00:40:46,004 --> 00:40:48,285
[GRYNSPAN]: So we need to include the private sector.

339
00:40:48,505 --> 00:40:55,271
[GRYNSPAN]: Obviously, we have to do our due diligence, but we won't lose independence in doing that.

340
00:40:55,391 --> 00:41:00,936
[GRYNSPAN]: On the contrary, if we don't do that, we will lose relevance.

341
00:41:01,497 --> 00:41:03,699
[GRYNSPAN]: And I think that that's really the challenge.

342
00:41:04,159 --> 00:41:12,907
[GRYNSPAN]: The UN has to learn how to partner with the private sector, not only in asking for resources, but in harnessing the capacities

343
00:41:13,267 --> 00:41:23,544
[GRYNSPAN]: and the knowledge that is there with them and with, as I said, civil society, regional organizations that can really help the UN to get better.

344
00:41:23,982 --> 00:41:24,542
[SPEAKER_10]: Well done.

345
00:41:24,602 --> 00:41:27,383
[SPEAKER_10]: So partnership with the private sector, absolutely crucial.

346
00:41:27,703 --> 00:41:33,844
[SPEAKER_10]: Carolyn, turning to you next, the UN, of course, we've heard is under growing financial pressure.

347
00:41:34,424 --> 00:41:36,664
[SPEAKER_10]: There's lots of reforms that are being put in place.

348
00:41:36,704 --> 00:41:38,745
[SPEAKER_10]: They remain a major challenge as well.

349
00:41:39,145 --> 00:41:46,206
[SPEAKER_10]: So as secretary general, what are the two areas that you would protect above and beyond at all costs?

350
00:41:46,646 --> 00:41:53,007
[SPEAKER_10]: And what is the one part of the system that you are prepared to change significantly?

351
00:41:54,721 --> 00:41:55,501
[RODRIGUES]: Thank you.

352
00:41:55,561 --> 00:41:57,742
[RODRIGUES]: That's giving a lot of power to the Secretary General.

353
00:41:58,643 --> 00:42:10,348
[RODRIGUES]: But let me say that what we have learned during this reform process is that the resident coordinator system on the ground has improved delivery

354
00:42:11,180 --> 00:42:11,840
[RODRIGUES]: by the UN.

355
00:42:12,581 --> 00:42:18,704
[RODRIGUES]: And I think that as we go forward in this reform process, we must protect that and we must strengthen that.

356
00:42:19,325 --> 00:42:26,709
[RODRIGUES]: And what I've been hearing as well from the largest donors to the UN is that they would like to see more impact on the ground.

357
00:42:27,309 --> 00:42:30,571
[RODRIGUES]: And this is one way of having impact on the ground.

358
00:42:31,051 --> 00:42:36,094
[RODRIGUES]: So I would say that is one thing that we should protect and we should strengthen.

359
00:42:36,950 --> 00:42:46,955
[RODRIGUES]: I wouldn't want to preempt the decision of member states in terms of the structural reforms, because that reform will change the face of what the UN looks like.

360
00:42:47,455 --> 00:42:57,240
[RODRIGUES]: But what I think is important to do is to make sure that member states have all the information that they need to make evidence-based decisions.

361
00:42:57,620 --> 00:43:00,642
[RODRIGUES]: So whether they decide to merge UN agencies

362
00:43:01,222 --> 00:43:08,107
[RODRIGUES]: or to merge functions, for example, that it must be guided by evidence-based information.

363
00:43:08,448 --> 00:43:11,510
[RODRIGUES]: So that is something that I would certainly want to see.

364
00:43:12,050 --> 00:43:19,116
[RODRIGUES]: Now, it is highly likely that by the time the new Secretary General is there, some of these decisions are already made.

365
00:43:19,576 --> 00:43:21,497
[RODRIGUES]: and so it's a matter of implementation.

366
00:43:21,997 --> 00:43:33,464
[RODRIGUES]: But I also believe that in any organization, much less one that is 80 years old, that reform must be a continuous process and adjustments must be a continuous process.

367
00:43:33,904 --> 00:43:43,350
[RODRIGUES]: The developments that we have seen over these last five, six years in terms of AI and so on, the developments before that would have taken decades.

368
00:43:43,630 --> 00:43:44,831
[RODRIGUES]: This one is just...

369
00:43:45,591 --> 00:43:47,373
[RODRIGUES]: took just a few years.

370
00:43:47,754 --> 00:43:52,400
[RODRIGUES]: And so we have to be prepared to be dynamic and to move with the times and to change with the times.

371
00:43:53,333 --> 00:43:53,753
[SPEAKER_10]: Wonderful.

372
00:43:53,813 --> 00:43:54,914
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that, Carolyn.

373
00:43:55,634 --> 00:44:06,958
[SPEAKER_10]: Finally, President Maguizal, of course, many countries in the Global South, yours included, argue that the UN still very much reflects the power structures of the past.

374
00:44:07,338 --> 00:44:15,100
[SPEAKER_10]: So what specific change would you make to the organization, as Secretary General, for it to be more responsible and more responsive?

375
00:44:15,661 --> 00:44:16,581
[SALL]: Thank you very much.

376
00:44:16,601 --> 00:44:19,822
[SALL]: I would like to start

377
00:44:21,460 --> 00:44:28,207
[SALL]: I would like to begin with the date of birth of the United Nations, 1945.

378
00:44:28,227 --> 00:44:30,329
[SALL]: We were 51 countries assigned.

379
00:44:34,485 --> 00:44:50,837
[SALL]: Now we are 193 countries and the organization is working still in the same way, which shows that there is a gap between what the world has become and what the organization used to be and that gap.

380
00:44:51,838 --> 00:44:59,724
[SALL]: It's even more important nowadays that we are facing even bigger challenges.

381
00:45:00,284 --> 00:45:10,291
[SALL]: Those tangible things are terrorism, for example, security-related challenges, artificial intelligence, the less access of peoples

382
00:45:13,433 --> 00:45:19,058
[SALL]: and to knowledge or financing also the violations of human rights.

383
00:45:19,578 --> 00:45:36,793
[SALL]: That is why we need to change the organization because it is an important platform and it is the only one and it is a universal platform that has a vocation to put the world around one table and to decide about the future of the world.

384
00:45:37,353 --> 00:46:01,789
[SALL]: And in order to bring about solutions to these challenges, I believe that we need a change, a shift in paradigm by a new redistribution, a fair redistribution, and it assumes that we have capital market access, financial markets,

385
00:46:02,389 --> 00:46:04,390
[SALL]: not only that, but also technologies.

386
00:46:04,710 --> 00:46:12,034
[SALL]: We talk a lot about artificial intelligence, but it shouldn't be something that is reserved to privileged countries.

387
00:46:12,094 --> 00:46:14,715
[SALL]: That is why we need to reform the organization.

388
00:46:14,735 --> 00:46:19,457
[SALL]: First of all, the secretariat, and then also the institution.

389
00:46:19,817 --> 00:46:30,963
[SALL]: But I believe also that member states have to participate in this reform, and of course, opening the Security Council and our working ways.

390
00:46:31,083 --> 00:46:31,763
[SALL]: Thank you very much.

391
00:46:32,043 --> 00:46:32,783
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

392
00:46:33,183 --> 00:46:36,244
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you all for keeping to your two minutes at the start.

393
00:46:36,404 --> 00:46:41,806
[SPEAKER_10]: And so importantly said, reallocating resources is needed at a time like this.

394
00:46:42,406 --> 00:46:50,128
[SPEAKER_10]: But we're now moving on very quickly, because we have limited time, of course, to the very important question of peace and security.

395
00:46:50,828 --> 00:47:06,051
[SPEAKER_10]: And in fact, the world, according to statistics, and of course you can turn the news on and you can find out yourself, is actually experiencing its highest number of armed conflicts since the end of the Second World War.

396
00:47:06,551 --> 00:47:14,453
[SPEAKER_10]: And this is a terrifying thing, and of course, which makes the role of the next Secretary General even more important and fundamental.

397
00:47:15,293 --> 00:47:16,253
[SPEAKER_10]: Maria, I'm turning to you.

398
00:47:16,633 --> 00:47:30,536
[SPEAKER_10]: Of all the crises, and there are many, as we know, facing the world today, what issue would be your top priority on day one in the job?

399
00:47:32,277 --> 00:47:44,079
[ESPINOSA]: My answer would be that you cannot rank conflicts to say this conflict is more important than conflict B or C. Every place where civilians suffer

400
00:47:45,225 --> 00:47:56,708
[ESPINOSA]: Every place where lives, livelihoods, hope, the future is hurt is the place for the United Nations to act and to act early.

401
00:47:58,429 --> 00:48:12,853
[ESPINOSA]: That's why my campaign and my narrative is about prevention, is about early engagement, is about prevention as a culture, as a way of operating within the system.

402
00:48:14,093 --> 00:48:23,980
[ESPINOSA]: I think the world wants to see a secretary general that is foot on the ground, that is present, that is persistent, that is where she needs to be.

403
00:48:24,781 --> 00:48:27,723
[ESPINOSA]: And of course, this is absolutely vital.

404
00:48:28,163 --> 00:48:30,905
[ESPINOSA]: When you look at what is happening in the world, you're right.

405
00:48:31,306 --> 00:48:36,109
[ESPINOSA]: We are living the highest numbers of armed conflicts since the Second World War.

406
00:48:36,669 --> 00:48:39,892
[ESPINOSA]: This means that perhaps the UN didn't prevent enough.

407
00:48:40,512 --> 00:48:44,196
[ESPINOSA]: didn't act early enough and did not respond enough.

408
00:48:44,816 --> 00:48:57,248
[ESPINOSA]: The responsibility of the Secretary General is to act early, to persist and be present, to deploy all the machinery and the infrastructure that the UN has on the ground

409
00:48:57,728 --> 00:49:03,049
[ESPINOSA]: to decrease the suffering of civilian people, to protect people.

410
00:49:03,389 --> 00:49:09,571
[ESPINOSA]: And when I say protect people, it includes also protecting the peacekeepers on the ground.

411
00:49:10,051 --> 00:49:18,513
[ESPINOSA]: We have seen yesterday an excellent resolution approved by the Security Council because the duty of the UN is to protect people

412
00:49:19,073 --> 00:49:24,861
[ESPINOSA]: to prevent conflict, to protect people, but also protect peacekeepers.

413
00:49:24,921 --> 00:49:37,257
[ESPINOSA]: And here, my thoughts with the Korean peacekeepers and with the 4,500 peacekeepers that have lost their lives serving under the UN flag.

414
00:49:37,677 --> 00:49:42,044
[ESPINOSA]: So no conflict is important than another conflict.

415
00:49:42,264 --> 00:49:51,098
[ESPINOSA]: All conflicts are the work of the UN, the responsibility of the UN, and the responsibility of a present Secretary General.

416
00:49:51,921 --> 00:49:52,762
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

417
00:49:53,222 --> 00:49:58,427
[SPEAKER_10]: Now moving on to the big nuclear issues, and of course we have the head of the IAEA himself right here.

418
00:49:59,047 --> 00:50:11,658
[SPEAKER_10]: The Security Council we know is increasingly divided, and of course nuclear risks are growing as we all know, including of course the ongoing challenges that are posed by North Korea in this region.

419
00:50:12,398 --> 00:50:18,444
[SPEAKER_10]: So how can the UN preserve and strengthen the global non-proliferation treaty?

420
00:50:19,024 --> 00:50:29,198
[GROSSI]: But we should remember that the creation of the UN comes in the wake of the use of nuclear weapons, and that the first resolution of the General Assembly was about it.

421
00:50:29,599 --> 00:50:35,687
[GROSSI]: We have to see, and perhaps it's a sobering conclusion, that 80 years after that,

422
00:50:36,237 --> 00:50:43,824
[GROSSI]: issue of nuclear weapons continue to haunt us and not in a way that seems to be going in the right direction.

423
00:50:44,645 --> 00:50:55,655
[GROSSI]: We see that after a period, a relatively long period of gradual decrease in nuclear arsenals, this has stopped.

424
00:50:55,995 --> 00:50:58,698
[GROSSI]: We see again the curve

425
00:51:00,299 --> 00:51:12,882
[GROSSI]: slowly but steadily picking up the issue, of course, which resonates so vividly here in this country of the DPRK, but not only there.

426
00:51:13,543 --> 00:51:28,667
[GROSSI]: The situations that we are trying to grapple with, coming from Burgenstock last weekend, where we are still trying to contain a problem before it becomes yet another

427
00:51:29,967 --> 00:51:34,209
[GROSSI]: case of proliferation of nuclear weapons.

428
00:51:34,790 --> 00:51:56,862
[GROSSI]: And what is also intriguing and concerning is that we listen more and more a conversation in countries that heretofore have abstained from having nuclear weapons, asking themselves whether this world, this fragmented world, does not warrant them reviewing

429
00:51:57,622 --> 00:52:13,087
[GROSSI]: that in some places some are saying well the protection between quotes that we are having from countries that do have nuclear weapons perhaps is not rock solid as we thought it was so shouldn't we

430
00:52:14,067 --> 00:52:15,388
[GROSSI]: have nuclear weapons.

431
00:52:15,568 --> 00:52:37,098
[GROSSI]: And believe you me, although we have a few countries, nine, having nuclear weapons, the world with the degree of conflictivity that we are having, and you are quoting the number of conflicts with 20, 25 of 37 countries with nuclear weapons, would be very, very dangerous indeed.

432
00:52:38,042 --> 00:52:38,982
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that message.

433
00:52:39,482 --> 00:52:44,724
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, Rebecca, a secretary general can, of course, act quietly behind the scenes.

434
00:52:44,764 --> 00:52:46,805
[SPEAKER_10]: You know, quiet diplomacy is truly powerful.

435
00:52:47,285 --> 00:52:49,745
[SPEAKER_10]: Or, of course, they could be acting very publicly.

436
00:52:49,986 --> 00:52:53,667
[SPEAKER_10]: So an easy question, but potentially a complex one for you.

437
00:52:54,407 --> 00:52:58,328
[SPEAKER_10]: What kind of diplomacy will you rely on most as secretary general?

438
00:52:59,493 --> 00:53:00,554
[GRYNSPAN]: No, thank you very much.

439
00:53:01,194 --> 00:53:16,645
[GRYNSPAN]: Let me first say that I have proposed the need to restructure the Office of the Secretary General precisely because I think that you cannot outsource mediation and you cannot outsource active diplomacy.

440
00:53:17,285 --> 00:53:26,832
[GRYNSPAN]: The Secretary General has to have the capacities in the Office of the Secretary General to be able to be active, to be present, to be visible, and to be effective.

441
00:53:27,232 --> 00:53:28,493
[GRYNSPAN]: So, first point.

442
00:53:29,133 --> 00:53:30,574
[GRYNSPAN]: Second point, it depends.

443
00:53:31,134 --> 00:53:33,015
[GRYNSPAN]: Let me give you two examples.

444
00:53:33,035 --> 00:53:43,680
[GRYNSPAN]: In Sudan right now, what we need to do is to put the spotlight in Sudan, because we know that what we see, we saw in Al-Fasher can happen again.

445
00:53:44,520 --> 00:53:46,302
[GRYNSPAN]: So what we need is to be visible.

446
00:53:46,362 --> 00:53:48,184
[GRYNSPAN]: What we need is to be outspoken.

447
00:53:48,244 --> 00:53:53,288
[GRYNSPAN]: What we need is to call for the attention on what is happening in Sudan.

448
00:53:53,589 --> 00:53:57,092
[GRYNSPAN]: We need to call for a humanitarian ceasefire immediately.

449
00:53:57,552 --> 00:54:04,299
[GRYNSPAN]: And the UN should be an actor that will allow more coordination in the different tracks.

450
00:54:04,839 --> 00:54:08,182
[GRYNSPAN]: that are today in negotiating.

451
00:54:08,242 --> 00:54:11,125
[GRYNSPAN]: So there are many tracks of negotiation.

452
00:54:11,425 --> 00:54:12,646
[GRYNSPAN]: There is no coordination.

453
00:54:13,046 --> 00:54:15,349
[GRYNSPAN]: So we need to call it out.

454
00:54:16,430 --> 00:54:29,782
[GRYNSPAN]: But, for example, in the Black Sea Initiative that, as you know, I negotiated with Russia, with Ukraine, and with Turkey, precisely for that problem, we needed quiet diplomacy.

455
00:54:30,462 --> 00:54:39,875
[GRYNSPAN]: We needed a diplomacy that first was able to talk to the actors, see what were the possibilities, and act accordingly.

456
00:54:40,275 --> 00:54:46,644
[GRYNSPAN]: So in that case, quiet diplomacy was necessary, much more discrete.

457
00:54:47,004 --> 00:55:04,868
[GRYNSPAN]: diplomacy, to be able to have a text to negotiate without exposing anybody and do that in a context where we were not ending the war, but we were avoiding a world food crisis within a war.

458
00:55:05,308 --> 00:55:11,530
[GRYNSPAN]: So we were able to get an agreement because quiet diplomacy was the way to go.

459
00:55:11,850 --> 00:55:19,252
[SPEAKER_10]: So a combination of both, and as you mentioned, the Black Sea Initiative, where, of course, Ukrainian grain was available to move again to the rest of the world.

460
00:55:19,692 --> 00:55:22,513
[SPEAKER_10]: Carolyn, you know, Rebecca just mentioned Sudan.

461
00:55:22,853 --> 00:55:32,955
[SPEAKER_10]: We know that conflicts in those places, Sudan, Myanmar, this region, and many others, of course, tend to fade from international headlines.

462
00:55:33,475 --> 00:55:35,996
[SPEAKER_10]: They don't get the international attention required.

463
00:55:36,376 --> 00:55:41,577
[SPEAKER_10]: So how would you ensure that long-running crises are not forgotten?

464
00:55:43,998 --> 00:55:46,159
[RODRIGUES]: I think there are several ways we can do this.

465
00:55:46,779 --> 00:55:59,625
[RODRIGUES]: One of the things that I've noticed is that while we may have a lot of discussions in the UN on a particular crisis, the media chooses which of these crises they want to highlight.

466
00:56:00,085 --> 00:56:04,447
[RODRIGUES]: And there are two or three of them that will be in the headlines all the time.

467
00:56:05,227 --> 00:56:14,054
[RODRIGUES]: And so I think that we have to find better ways, the Secretary General in particular, to communicate, to communicate what is happening out there.

468
00:56:14,675 --> 00:56:20,900
[RODRIGUES]: Because as we have seen in recent times, there's nothing like a frozen crisis any day one.

469
00:56:21,560 --> 00:56:25,004
[RODRIGUES]: can just come at it at the top of the agenda.

470
00:56:25,665 --> 00:56:29,830
[RODRIGUES]: And so communication, I think, it's very, very important to do that.

471
00:56:30,151 --> 00:56:32,814
[RODRIGUES]: But not only the Secretary General.

472
00:56:33,174 --> 00:56:37,319
[RODRIGUES]: We have all 193 member states represented at the UN.

473
00:56:38,020 --> 00:56:46,862
[RODRIGUES]: And I think that discussion with member states, whether it's in smaller groups, a crisis from a particular area, discussing with them.

474
00:56:47,303 --> 00:56:53,404
[RODRIGUES]: And I've seen member states use the platforms at the UN as well to promote different issues.

475
00:56:53,664 --> 00:57:06,288
[RODRIGUES]: And this is one way I think we can work together, the Secretary General and member states, to keep these, I wouldn't call them forgotten, but those that do not get the kind of global attention that they need.

476
00:57:06,888 --> 00:57:19,196
[RODRIGUES]: But I'm also conscious that there are times when you have to choose whether you're going to make a public statement or you're going to do things quietly to allow for solutions to progress.

477
00:57:19,776 --> 00:57:32,864
[RODRIGUES]: And I think one has to discern when that is necessary because I've also seen cases where when you come out too quickly with a public statement, you remove yourself from being part of the solution as Secretary General.

478
00:57:33,364 --> 00:57:35,486
[RODRIGUES]: And so, as I said, discernment,

479
00:57:36,266 --> 00:57:41,389
[RODRIGUES]: versatility and knowing which of the options you should choose for each one.

480
00:57:42,370 --> 00:57:43,530
[SPEAKER_10]: Good response, thank you.

481
00:57:43,630 --> 00:57:45,271
[SPEAKER_10]: And within two minutes too, excellent.

482
00:57:46,052 --> 00:57:55,417
[SPEAKER_10]: Now moving to another question and again reflecting on what Secretary General Ban Ki-moon said earlier, you know, the role of the Secretary General is so difficult.

483
00:57:55,517 --> 00:57:59,800
[SPEAKER_10]: It's an unenviable role and he doesn't envy you guys for going up for it.

484
00:58:00,500 --> 00:58:04,903
[SPEAKER_10]: There's so many difficult choices that the Secretary General has to make for the UN.

485
00:58:05,843 --> 00:58:11,009
[SPEAKER_10]: So how would you choose to invest the political energy?

486
00:58:11,450 --> 00:58:19,740
[SPEAKER_10]: Which crises do you think will deserve the UN's immediate attention and resources once you take office?

487
00:58:22,774 --> 00:58:40,114
[SPEAKER_06]: The first ever is to give a certain hierarchy among these different crises, because there are so many crises that threaten the peace and that requires our whole attention, and every crisis

488
00:58:42,635 --> 00:58:50,259
[SPEAKER_06]: that makes human suffer and that has an impact on the economic world is important.

489
00:58:50,299 --> 00:58:53,840
[SPEAKER_06]: So we should not rank different crises.

490
00:58:54,501 --> 00:59:07,627
[SPEAKER_06]: And, for example, the war in Sudan where several thousand, hundreds of millions of people die and who become refugees who suffer in

491
00:59:08,047 --> 00:59:10,870
[SPEAKER_06]: extreme conditions that should not be forgotten.

492
00:59:10,890 --> 00:59:16,815
[SALL]: And all these crises all over the world are important.

493
00:59:16,956 --> 00:59:24,002
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course, there are crises that are bigger in, for example, the crisis in Israel.

494
00:59:25,944 --> 00:59:27,785
[SPEAKER_06]: and also the Hormuz Strait.

495
00:59:28,625 --> 00:59:43,410
[SPEAKER_06]: Those are big crises that have a big consequence on the global economic environment, of course, and we can think about the Russia-Ukraine crisis and different climate change.

496
00:59:44,430 --> 00:59:59,474
[SPEAKER_06]: We can think about bigger crises that also get a lot of attention from the media, but we should use all our diplomatic network and all our resources to prevent these conflicts and crises.

497
00:59:59,494 --> 01:00:05,896
[SPEAKER_06]: And this is the work that the Secretary General has to do, and it's the work of the UN.

498
01:00:06,256 --> 01:00:11,597
[SPEAKER_06]: So therefore, we have to rebuild the trust between the member states of the UN.

499
01:00:13,539 --> 01:00:29,593
[SPEAKER_06]: And we have to build the trust so that we can, in a responsible manner, fight against this crisis and to bring our whole world towards a future that is more stable.

500
01:00:31,384 --> 01:00:32,124
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

501
01:00:32,585 --> 01:00:39,327
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, absolutely, having to allocate all those resources to every crisis in the world is a difficult one, and rebuilding trust.

502
01:00:39,747 --> 01:00:47,730
[SPEAKER_10]: And speaking of rebuilding trust, we're moving on to our final theme, and that is, of course, the reason why we have so many young people amongst us in the audience.

503
01:00:47,850 --> 01:01:00,394
[SPEAKER_10]: It's about, of course, coming up with issues at the UN and elsewhere around technology, around development, around climate, that will impact not only the world, but

504
01:01:00,774 --> 01:01:08,721
[SPEAKER_10]: future generations, and this is why it's so important to be a part of this conversation that includes the young.

505
01:01:10,002 --> 01:01:19,289
[SPEAKER_10]: So Maria Fernanda Espinosa, young people are not only demanding change from outside the UN, many are already working from within the system.

506
01:01:19,790 --> 01:01:24,834
[SPEAKER_10]: How would you ensure that younger staff have a stronger voice in shaping the UN's future?

507
01:01:28,423 --> 01:01:33,846
[ESPINOSA]: Well, I think I try to move away from the tokenistic approach.

508
01:01:34,006 --> 01:01:36,747
[ESPINOSA]: Yes, young people should participate.

509
01:01:37,247 --> 01:01:39,008
[ESPINOSA]: They should be part of the solution.

510
01:01:39,629 --> 01:01:45,492
[ESPINOSA]: My experience shows me that the most efficient teams are intergenerational teams.

511
01:01:46,752 --> 01:01:53,755
[ESPINOSA]: to combine wisdom, institutional memory with innovation and cutting-edge knowledge.

512
01:01:54,195 --> 01:01:59,837
[ESPINOSA]: So the way you build your teams has to be intergenerational.

513
01:01:59,877 --> 01:02:05,739
[ESPINOSA]: Number two, younger staff members should not inherit UN as it is.

514
01:02:06,179 --> 01:02:11,341
[ESPINOSA]: They should be part of the new design and the constant reform of the organization.

515
01:02:11,861 --> 01:02:19,047
[ESPINOSA]: Number three, they should receive what they need in terms of a career development plan.

516
01:02:19,087 --> 01:02:22,409
[ESPINOSA]: This looks like common sense, but it doesn't happen.

517
01:02:23,110 --> 01:02:37,661
[ESPINOSA]: A career development plan, a skills development plan, to make sure that they are going to be fit for the role they're going to play and to really be committed with a high morale and with a sense of mission.

518
01:02:38,101 --> 01:02:39,522
[ESPINOSA]: And I think that goes

519
01:02:40,783 --> 01:02:46,486
[ESPINOSA]: you know, well with the UN staff, because they are the most qualified and the most committed.

520
01:02:46,926 --> 01:02:52,609
[ESPINOSA]: And I think we need the human talent of the UN, and of course, young human talent.

521
01:02:52,949 --> 01:02:56,051
[ESPINOSA]: Believe me, it's not an issue of looking good or of optics.

522
01:02:56,511 --> 01:03:03,034
[ESPINOSA]: It is that intergenerational teams are more impactful and provide better results.

523
01:03:03,094 --> 01:03:09,758
[ESPINOSA]: So of course, my team, when Secretary General, my own team and my own office,

524
01:03:10,178 --> 01:03:12,059
[ESPINOSA]: is going to be intergenerational.

525
01:03:12,379 --> 01:03:17,381
[ESPINOSA]: If you look at my team now, most of my advisors are under 30.

526
01:03:17,801 --> 01:03:19,802
[ESPINOSA]: And one is standing over there, actually.

527
01:03:20,542 --> 01:03:21,543
[ESPINOSA]: They are below 30.

528
01:03:21,583 --> 01:03:29,586
[ESPINOSA]: So I fully trust the creativity, the innovation, the wisdom, the transformational capacity of younger generations.

529
01:03:29,987 --> 01:03:30,767
[SPEAKER_10]: Wonderfully said.

530
01:03:30,807 --> 01:03:33,288
[SPEAKER_10]: And of course, if any of you are looking to join, there you go.

531
01:03:33,308 --> 01:03:35,569
[SPEAKER_10]: You can look in your cabinet if you do get the role.

532
01:03:37,490 --> 01:03:43,493
[SPEAKER_10]: Of course, some young people, and we've been talking a lot about this, they've lost their trust in institutions like the UN.

533
01:03:43,914 --> 01:03:50,357
[SPEAKER_10]: How would you rebuild trust and give young people a real crucial role in the organization?

534
01:03:50,937 --> 01:03:53,799
[GROSSI]: First of all, they need to understand what's going on, because they don't.

535
01:03:54,479 --> 01:03:55,380
[GROSSI]: And I don't blame them.

536
01:03:56,798 --> 01:04:06,506
[GROSSI]: As a father of eight young adults and one teenager, I can tell you that the UN does not exist in their world.

537
01:04:06,826 --> 01:04:08,388
[GROSSI]: They don't care about the UN.

538
01:04:08,408 --> 01:04:11,050
[GROSSI]: And the UN basically does not care for them.

539
01:04:11,530 --> 01:04:13,432
[GROSSI]: For everything we can say, all these phrases.

540
01:04:13,632 --> 01:04:15,593
[GROSSI]: you were saying, you know, we have all these slogans.

541
01:04:17,795 --> 01:04:25,420
[GROSSI]: The younger generations either don't understand, don't see the UN or don't care.

542
01:04:25,800 --> 01:04:28,882
[GROSSI]: And so we should ask ourselves the tough questions.

543
01:04:29,642 --> 01:04:30,823
[GROSSI]: Why is this?

544
01:04:32,144 --> 01:04:36,527
[GROSSI]: One very important aspect, I believe, is also communication.

545
01:04:37,047 --> 01:04:41,170
[GROSSI]: And I don't think we communicate because there are things that are important

546
01:04:41,610 --> 01:04:54,136
[GROSSI]: for the younger generations that need to be transmitted, that they are transmitting in a very poor way, in a way that does not resonate and not through the channels that they use these days.

547
01:04:54,396 --> 01:05:01,139
[GROSSI]: So this is, as a communicator yourself, this is a very, very important aspect, how we tell the story.

548
01:05:03,861 --> 01:05:10,785
[GROSSI]: I don't believe that the issues of youth are solved with the creation of offices in the United Nations.

549
01:05:11,245 --> 01:05:15,168
[GROSSI]: I don't think that is the way that doesn't move the needle.

550
01:05:17,750 --> 01:05:20,672
[GROSSI]: Policies and good policies are by definition

551
01:05:21,432 --> 01:05:22,833
[GROSSI]: for the younger generation.

552
01:05:22,853 --> 01:05:31,138
[GROSSI]: When we are looking at the SDGs that Secretary Ban Ki-moon left us, who are these for?

553
01:05:31,719 --> 01:05:39,884
[GROSSI]: I mean, when we talk about getting rid of nuclear weapons or preventing nuclear weapons or solving issues related to hunger or poverty or health,

554
01:05:40,324 --> 01:05:43,307
[GROSSI]: we are doing this for the younger generation.

555
01:05:43,607 --> 01:05:54,518
[GROSSI]: So I believe that trust is going to be rebuilt quite spontaneously the day they see that the UN is really solving issues and they understand how this is done.

556
01:05:55,361 --> 01:06:03,166
[SPEAKER_10]: Absolutely, and I hope that once you, and if you become Secretary General, your eight children will start to pay attention to what happens at the UN.

557
01:06:03,687 --> 01:06:11,672
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, Rebecca, for many young people, of course, one of the key themes we've been talking about for this entire Jeju forum is multilateralism.

558
01:06:12,012 --> 01:06:20,158
[SPEAKER_10]: So how would you convince young people that multilateralism truly matters and the UN truly matters in their daily lives?

559
01:06:21,798 --> 01:06:36,359
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, first of all, I will agree that we will rebuild their trust and we will convince them that multilateralism is important and what we do is important if we address the problem that they really face today.

560
01:06:37,781 --> 01:06:39,422
[GRYNSPAN]: They are worried about their jobs.

561
01:06:39,602 --> 01:06:41,623
[GRYNSPAN]: They are worried about quality jobs.

562
01:06:41,863 --> 01:06:49,986
[GRYNSPAN]: One in five young people today in the world have informal jobs, not quality jobs.

563
01:06:50,346 --> 01:06:51,567
[GRYNSPAN]: They are not in training.

564
01:06:51,667 --> 01:06:53,148
[GRYNSPAN]: They are not in education.

565
01:06:53,668 --> 01:06:57,049
[GRYNSPAN]: So they want to see us solving that problem.

566
01:06:57,089 --> 01:07:05,953
[GRYNSPAN]: They want to see us solving the problems of war that are displacing them from their own homes, from their own families.

567
01:07:06,313 --> 01:07:10,914
[GRYNSPAN]: So I agree that the first thing is to address the problems that they face.

568
01:07:11,814 --> 01:07:18,696
[GRYNSPAN]: But we also have this problem in the UN and, you know, we have a problem.

569
01:07:22,056 --> 01:07:30,218
[GRYNSPAN]: I ask you, do you know what is the percentage of people under 30 in the UN staff?

570
01:07:32,983 --> 01:07:36,807
[GRYNSPAN]: I guess four percent.

571
01:07:37,268 --> 01:07:37,948
[GRYNSPAN]: Four percent.

572
01:07:38,829 --> 01:07:46,297
[GRYNSPAN]: We have closed the doors of the UN to young people and I think that that is our first task.

573
01:07:46,698 --> 01:07:49,221
[GRYNSPAN]: We need to open the doors again for them.

574
01:07:49,601 --> 01:07:52,104
[GRYNSPAN]: They cannot even apply for the jobs.

575
01:07:52,504 --> 01:08:05,498
[GRYNSPAN]: You know, even the first entry point to the UN has been really almost non-existent in the last period because of financial problems.

576
01:08:06,038 --> 01:08:14,748
[GRYNSPAN]: So the exams for the underrepresented countries where the young people can come to the UN has not even take place.

577
01:08:15,348 --> 01:08:26,923
[GRYNSPAN]: So let's open the doors of the UN for young people, for them to be part of the stuff, part of the innovation, part of the idea, part of what we do every day.

578
01:08:27,243 --> 01:08:28,665
[GRYNSPAN]: So they will change the world.

579
01:08:29,066 --> 01:08:29,647
[SPEAKER_10]: Absolutely.

580
01:08:29,687 --> 01:08:31,729
[SPEAKER_10]: And of course, yes, applause, please.

581
01:08:32,730 --> 01:08:38,393
[SPEAKER_10]: And we need to raise that dismally low statistic, 4% of young people at the UN.

582
01:08:38,913 --> 01:08:42,595
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, Carolyn, of course, young people stand to benefit enormously.

583
01:08:42,635 --> 01:08:44,656
[SPEAKER_10]: In fact, we all do, from AI.

584
01:08:44,716 --> 01:08:47,517
[SPEAKER_10]: This is something that we've talked about a lot at this forum as well.

585
01:08:47,858 --> 01:08:49,999
[SPEAKER_10]: And responsible AI in particular.

586
01:08:50,019 --> 01:08:52,600
[SPEAKER_10]: But of course, young people could also not benefit

587
01:08:52,800 --> 01:08:53,780
[SPEAKER_10]: fit from AI.

588
01:08:53,800 --> 01:08:58,582
[SPEAKER_10]: There are so many jobs that may be of course non-existence for them in the future.

589
01:08:58,642 --> 01:09:05,785
[SPEAKER_10]: So how would you ensure that young voices will help shape the rules on artificial intelligence?

590
01:09:07,866 --> 01:09:08,266
[RODRIGUES]: Thank you.

591
01:09:09,772 --> 01:09:14,175
[RODRIGUES]: I think that there are different ways that we can do this.

592
01:09:14,195 --> 01:09:20,479
[RODRIGUES]: And just to come back to the point made earlier, I think there are two ways that we should engage young people.

593
01:09:20,619 --> 01:09:30,305
[RODRIGUES]: One is getting young people in the UN system, but also in all of the processes that the UN is involved in, young people must be consulted.

594
01:09:30,965 --> 01:09:38,710
[RODRIGUES]: So as shapers and also as contributors to policies that the UN is involved in.

595
01:09:39,630 --> 01:09:51,642
[RODRIGUES]: I was involved, and I know Rafael says he doesn't like the creation of offices, but I was one of the co-facilitators that facilitated the process to establish the youth office.

596
01:09:52,418 --> 01:09:54,079
[RODRIGUES]: of the UN.

597
01:09:54,099 --> 01:09:57,541
[RODRIGUES]: And we had a consultation in Zoom.

598
01:09:57,701 --> 01:10:10,448
[RODRIGUES]: 350 young people signed in from all over the world and contributed to that process and shaped that process and demanded that the head of that office is not older than 35 years old.

599
01:10:10,768 --> 01:10:12,789
[RODRIGUES]: So that was one very good example.

600
01:10:13,429 --> 01:10:17,472
[RODRIGUES]: In the AI governance, again, we must involve them because I think

601
01:10:18,612 --> 01:10:20,113
[RODRIGUES]: not as onlookers only.

602
01:10:20,753 --> 01:10:28,736
[RODRIGUES]: They're the ones, I think, that are more prone to using the technology and showing us how this could be beneficial for our world.

603
01:10:29,076 --> 01:10:36,059
[RODRIGUES]: The older ones are sometimes a bit hesitant about new technology, but I think young people, they're able to tell us.

604
01:10:36,919 --> 01:10:44,404
[RODRIGUES]: And one thing I've noticed in my time, and I'm still not so old, it would take 10 years to accumulate a certain amount of knowledge.

605
01:10:44,684 --> 01:10:46,665
[RODRIGUES]: That now is in the hands of young people.

606
01:10:47,126 --> 01:10:49,767
[RODRIGUES]: And I think they're good at analysis as well.

607
01:10:50,328 --> 01:11:00,394
[RODRIGUES]: And so I agree that we shouldn't be tokenistic toward young people, as Maria said, and involve them fully in the AI governance discussion.

608
01:11:00,694 --> 01:11:05,157
[RODRIGUES]: And I know that that discussion is a difficult one, but we must have young people in that as well.

609
01:11:05,777 --> 01:11:06,777
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

610
01:11:07,538 --> 01:11:20,361
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, President Makisal, with 2030 approaching, we know that will be the end of the Sustainable Development Goals and we know they will remain off track by the time we hit that target.

611
01:11:20,781 --> 01:11:29,763
[SPEAKER_10]: So what would come after the SDGs and what should the central priority of the next global development agenda be?

612
01:11:34,463 --> 01:11:39,205
[SALL]: Thank you very much.

613
01:11:39,385 --> 01:11:56,389
[SALL]: After the MDGs, we followed them with the SDGs and also to fight against poverty and to protect the planet and, of course, the environment.

614
01:11:56,749 --> 01:12:01,730
[SALL]: However, nowadays, the question that we have to ask ourselves is what are the challenges

615
01:12:02,310 --> 01:12:03,610
[SALL]: after 2030.

616
01:12:03,731 --> 01:12:13,293
[SALL]: I think that the challenges we will be facing after 2030 is resilience, mostly.

617
01:12:14,854 --> 01:12:24,117
[SALL]: Resilience facing shocks that are becoming more frequent, climatic shocks, also sanitary

618
01:12:25,359 --> 01:12:34,529
[SALL]: Shocks, especially after the pandemic, shocks because of the lack of financing, because of the lack of opportunities.

619
01:12:35,110 --> 01:12:37,673
[SALL]: How can we organize this resilience?

620
01:12:37,833 --> 01:12:40,596
[SALL]: How can we build this resilience?

621
01:12:40,696 --> 01:12:45,882
[SALL]: I believe that we need to put in place a global consortium

622
01:12:48,463 --> 01:13:07,548
[SALL]: so that we can go above and beyond the 2030 agenda in order to bring about the righteous answers, also in terms of financing for developing countries

623
01:13:10,090 --> 01:13:23,242
[SALL]: And also, that way, with all other countries and member states, after 2030, we'll be able to set new goals and go towards them.

624
01:13:25,731 --> 01:13:31,334
[SALL]: If I had one more minute talking about youth, I could talk about two things.

625
01:13:31,474 --> 01:13:40,679
[SALL]: First of all, the organization that is the United Nations has to open more channels and give more opportunities to the youth.

626
01:13:40,699 --> 01:13:45,662
[SALL]: But most important, among all the human beings, the population

627
01:13:46,742 --> 01:13:54,028
[SALL]: that we have on our planet, about one third of them do not have the adequate education.

628
01:13:54,648 --> 01:14:00,192
[SALL]: So we have to take care of the jobs for our young people.

629
01:14:00,212 --> 01:14:01,053
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

630
01:14:01,113 --> 01:14:09,359
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, absolutely, because the SDGs are so fundamental for the world that we create, that the world that the future generations will inherit.

631
01:14:09,780 --> 01:14:13,742
[SPEAKER_10]: And speaking about those future generations, we have them here in the audience.

632
01:14:14,563 --> 01:14:20,687
[SPEAKER_10]: We can now move to the questions that some of them are posing to the future Secretary-General.

633
01:14:20,787 --> 01:14:31,074
[SPEAKER_10]: So let me now go to our first question, which comes from Choi Hyerin, a bachelor's graduate from Jeju Halla University.

634
01:14:32,075 --> 01:14:33,896
[SPEAKER_10]: Hyerin, I believe you're here somewhere.

635
01:14:34,797 --> 01:14:40,461
[SPEAKER_10]: Can we have the microphone for you and can you pose your question to the candidates, please?

636
01:14:44,285 --> 01:14:45,447
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, do we have a microphone?

637
01:14:47,972 --> 01:14:48,873
[SPEAKER_10]: I believe I see you there.

638
01:14:48,913 --> 01:14:49,374
[SPEAKER_10]: Is that you?

639
01:14:49,495 --> 01:14:50,216
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, perfect.

640
01:14:50,276 --> 01:14:51,939
[SPEAKER_10]: Can somebody get her a microphone, please?

641
01:14:55,365 --> 01:14:55,946
[SPEAKER_10]: Can somebody there?

642
01:14:56,227 --> 01:14:56,667
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

643
01:14:57,921 --> 01:14:59,642
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you for this opportunity.

644
01:15:00,703 --> 01:15:13,309
[SPEAKER_07]: As a young entrepreneur in the cultural and creative sector, I frequently see how culture bridges divides far more easily than traditional politics.

645
01:15:13,850 --> 01:15:21,794
[SPEAKER_07]: So given today's intense geopolitical fragmentation, how would you as Secretary General

646
01:15:22,194 --> 01:15:37,438
[SPEAKER_07]: strategically use the cultural and creative industries as a tool to rebuild trust between conflicting nations and revitalize multilateralism from the ground up.

647
01:15:37,918 --> 01:15:38,438
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

648
01:15:39,358 --> 01:15:40,138
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, Hyerin.

649
01:15:40,218 --> 01:15:43,119
[SPEAKER_10]: And this is, of course, open to all of you who would like to respond.

650
01:15:43,919 --> 01:15:45,679
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, Maria, followed by Rebecca.

651
01:15:46,920 --> 01:15:47,780
[SPEAKER_10]: Maria, you start first.

652
01:15:48,615 --> 01:15:48,895
[ESPINOSA]: Okay.

653
01:15:49,796 --> 01:15:53,699
[ESPINOSA]: Well, first of all, thank you for that very important question.

654
01:15:53,899 --> 01:15:57,142
[ESPINOSA]: Sometimes people say that culture is soft power.

655
01:15:58,363 --> 01:16:10,312
[ESPINOSA]: I think culture and intercultural dialogue and the possibility of understanding the diversity of perspectives should be the hardcore of diplomacy and dialogue.

656
01:16:10,632 --> 01:16:12,373
[ESPINOSA]: So it's extremely important.

657
01:16:13,254 --> 01:16:17,818
[ESPINOSA]: Believe me, when I was president of the General Assembly, the day I think I was the most

658
01:16:18,518 --> 01:16:23,085
[ESPINOSA]: popular is when I invited BTS to join me.

659
01:16:23,706 --> 01:16:34,562
[ESPINOSA]: The K-pop culture of Korea has gone all over the world and brought a mutual understanding, energy, the ability

660
01:16:35,002 --> 01:16:55,651
[ESPINOSA]: to speak to different cultures, not to speak about Korean series, which are at the heart of my own family household, but to say that a culture builds bridges is the hardcore, not the soft power, but the strong power of diplomacy and mutual understanding.

661
01:16:55,771 --> 01:16:58,572
[ESPINOSA]: The role of UNESCO is absolutely critical

662
01:16:59,372 --> 01:17:07,982
[ESPINOSA]: And as Secretary General, I will ensure that intercultural dialogue, that culture itself is at the center of the work we do.

663
01:17:08,781 --> 01:17:09,441
[SPEAKER_10]: Absolutely.

664
01:17:09,501 --> 01:17:11,782
[SPEAKER_10]: And who can beat Korean culture, right?

665
01:17:11,822 --> 01:17:14,263
[SPEAKER_10]: Demon hunters, BTS, you name it.

666
01:17:15,023 --> 01:17:15,403
[SPEAKER_10]: Rebecca?

667
01:17:16,543 --> 01:17:20,904
[GRYNSPAN]: Can I just make the comment that I am freezing here?

668
01:17:20,924 --> 01:17:23,065
[GRYNSPAN]: Not great for climate change.

669
01:17:23,865 --> 01:17:24,685
[GRYNSPAN]: No, no, no, no.

670
01:17:24,705 --> 01:17:30,227
[GRYNSPAN]: It's because we women have a lower blood pressure, you know?

671
01:17:30,247 --> 01:17:34,048
[GRYNSPAN]: So the problem is who controls the air conditioning?

672
01:17:35,729 --> 01:17:38,330
[SPEAKER_10]: Please, can we bring the temperature up, please?

673
01:17:42,113 --> 01:17:45,135
[GRYNSPAN]: Let me just go to the question of the young lady.

674
01:17:47,196 --> 01:18:00,625
[GRYNSPAN]: Let me first say that I was really glad about your question because when I reformed ANTAT, we created a special department on creative industries.

675
01:18:01,928 --> 01:18:13,650
[GRYNSPAN]: And I think that this is a very powerful tool, not only to maintain culture, but to allow all the workers in the cultural space to really make a living.

676
01:18:14,231 --> 01:18:16,231
[GRYNSPAN]: And it's very important for small countries.

677
01:18:16,311 --> 01:18:19,992
[GRYNSPAN]: It's very important for the islands, for example.

678
01:18:21,092 --> 01:18:26,073
[GRYNSPAN]: And really, creative industries are a huge part of the economy.

679
01:18:26,633 --> 01:18:41,499
[GRYNSPAN]: but it's not accounted for, it's not measured, and so many times we don't take the right decisions and the right policies with respect to supporting the cultural workers and the cultural actors in the country.

680
01:18:42,019 --> 01:18:51,543
[GRYNSPAN]: My second point, and I will completely agree with Maria on this, is that really culture allows us to share humanity.

681
01:18:52,063 --> 01:19:14,949
[GRYNSPAN]: Yes, is really a space where we can understand each other, we can communicate, we can exchange, and we can do something that is very central to peace, that is allow for inclusive identities, to bring to your own identity many of the other expressions in the other cultures.

682
01:19:15,069 --> 01:19:20,790
[GRYNSPAN]: So, really great, and thank you, thank you for bringing that to the floor.

683
01:19:21,430 --> 01:19:26,991
[SPEAKER_10]: We'll move to our next question and I have to say creative industries, as you say, intangible benefits of creative industries.

684
01:19:27,051 --> 01:19:32,912
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm a chancellor of a university that celebrates creative industries, so very, very excited about the potential for that.

685
01:19:33,353 --> 01:19:35,413
[SPEAKER_10]: Next up we have Musa Elhem.

686
01:19:35,453 --> 01:19:39,554
[SPEAKER_10]: Musa is a master's student from Sungkyunkwan University.

687
01:19:39,594 --> 01:19:44,115
[SPEAKER_10]: You have a question and I hope we can get the mic to you quickly because we are running out of time.

688
01:19:44,335 --> 01:19:44,655
[SPEAKER_10]: Musa.

689
01:19:47,853 --> 01:19:53,939
[SPEAKER_15]: Trust in multilateral institutions is declining, especially among young generation.

690
01:19:54,279 --> 01:20:05,509
[SPEAKER_15]: So my question is, what is the first concrete change you would make as a secretary general in your first year to make them believe that the UN works for them?

691
01:20:07,191 --> 01:20:07,691
[SPEAKER_10]: Absolutely.

692
01:20:08,071 --> 01:20:10,754
[RODRIGUES]: Let's start with you, Carolyn, followed by Magiselle.

693
01:20:11,835 --> 01:20:13,156
[RODRIGUES]: Thank you for that question.

694
01:20:13,236 --> 01:20:14,077
[RODRIGUES]: And I think that

695
01:20:15,625 --> 01:20:24,184
[RODRIGUES]: We have failed you, actually, and all the young people in not telling the story of the UN and the achievements of the UN.

696
01:20:25,149 --> 01:20:32,252
[RODRIGUES]: Many do not know that when they fly in an aeroplane, that the rules of the sky, the UN is involved in that.

697
01:20:33,093 --> 01:20:36,974
[RODRIGUES]: That the food standards that we set, that it is the UN there.

698
01:20:37,495 --> 01:20:42,517
[RODRIGUES]: That the first responders sometimes in the humanitarian field, it's the UN there.

699
01:20:43,097 --> 01:20:48,200
[RODRIGUES]: That the children and the improvement in education for them, that it was the UN there as well.

700
01:20:48,620 --> 01:20:50,881
[RODRIGUES]: And so we have failed in communicating that.

701
01:20:51,401 --> 01:20:52,722
[RODRIGUES]: And as we're in the 80th year,

702
01:20:53,682 --> 01:20:57,167
[RODRIGUES]: The people who witnessed war back then, they have passed on.

703
01:20:57,788 --> 01:21:08,081
[RODRIGUES]: And so I think communication is important in terms of what the UN has done, but also in terms of the challenges we face and the solutions as well.

704
01:21:08,962 --> 01:21:12,705
[RODRIGUES]: and how young people can be involved in those solutions.

705
01:21:13,205 --> 01:21:23,352
[RODRIGUES]: Because one of the things that is overlooked sometimes is that the UN is the place where we set the norms of the world that we all agree to live by.

706
01:21:23,912 --> 01:21:26,995
[RODRIGUES]: And the UN is irreplaceable in that respect.

707
01:21:27,155 --> 01:21:30,137
[RODRIGUES]: There's no other organization that can do that.

708
01:21:30,577 --> 01:21:39,342
[RODRIGUES]: And so I think communication is important for us to make you believe in multilateralism, but also for you to choose diplomacy.

709
01:21:39,862 --> 01:21:40,402
[SALL]: Thank you.

710
01:21:40,702 --> 01:21:44,324
[SALL]: Macky.

711
01:21:44,624 --> 01:21:49,947
[SALL]: In fact, we do have a communication issue with the youth, with the young people.

712
01:21:50,347 --> 01:21:54,850
[SALL]: However, the UN for the last 80 years did a lot

713
01:21:57,278 --> 01:22:05,201
[SALL]: Without the actions of the UN, I believe that the wars would be even more devastating.

714
01:22:06,042 --> 01:22:14,125
[SALL]: I believe that we were able to avoid a lot of conflicts and a lot of wars because of the work that we made at the UN.

715
01:22:14,485 --> 01:22:18,807
[SALL]: And every time we discuss an issue,

716
01:22:20,428 --> 01:22:24,731
[SALL]: at the UN, it is because we want the humanity to advance.

717
01:22:24,831 --> 01:22:37,920
[SALL]: Every time we develop a vaccine, it's for the health of the world, and it is for the young people, the young people that communicate and live throughout social media and also very new phenomena.

718
01:22:38,421 --> 01:22:46,807
[SALL]: And I believe that the institutional classic and also very old and demoted communication has to change.

719
01:22:47,747 --> 01:23:01,627
[SALL]: And I believe that what UN does is actually for the purpose and for the future of the new generation, except that we need to communicate that by language that the young people understand.

720
01:23:02,408 --> 01:23:03,288
[SPEAKER_10]: Education is key.

721
01:23:03,328 --> 01:23:05,529
[SPEAKER_10]: We need to earn the trust of the young people.

722
01:23:06,189 --> 01:23:12,151
[SPEAKER_10]: We quickly have two last questions from the young people in the audience, and then, of course, we are going to have to wrap up with the concluding remarks.

723
01:23:12,451 --> 01:23:19,233
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm going to go now to Duggajin Osmanaj, who's a prospective graduate student from Songkyun Kwan University.

724
01:23:19,293 --> 01:23:20,974
[SPEAKER_10]: Duggajin, you have a question?

725
01:23:22,455 --> 01:23:22,675
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

726
01:23:23,215 --> 01:23:23,675
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

727
01:23:25,008 --> 01:23:32,412
[SPEAKER_09]: The 2020s have shown that we live in a time when wars are becoming more frequent and international norms are being increasingly challenged.

728
01:23:33,292 --> 01:23:35,894
[SPEAKER_09]: This decade can also be called the decade of AI.

729
01:23:36,414 --> 01:23:49,400
[SPEAKER_09]: So my question is just simply, do you think AI can positively aid the UN, stopping conflicts from escalating, and if so, how?

730
01:23:50,522 --> 01:23:51,502
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, who would like to take that?

731
01:23:51,542 --> 01:23:53,523
[SPEAKER_10]: Rafael, would you like to mention that?

732
01:23:53,963 --> 01:23:55,844
[GROSSI]: It can, and it can bring problems.

733
01:23:55,904 --> 01:23:57,385
[GROSSI]: I mean, it's a double-edged sword.

734
01:23:57,545 --> 01:24:01,507
[GROSSI]: I think it is very clear that AI is already in our lives.

735
01:24:01,587 --> 01:24:04,628
[GROSSI]: We talk about it as it was something that is coming.

736
01:24:05,248 --> 01:24:07,149
[GROSSI]: It's already in everything we do.

737
01:24:07,609 --> 01:24:13,552
[GROSSI]: There are debates within the UN and international organisations as to how to

738
01:24:14,852 --> 01:24:16,133
[GROSSI]: govern it or control it.

739
01:24:17,513 --> 01:24:28,898
[GROSSI]: And there are already, from the supply side, groupings that have already been established among the companies or

740
01:24:30,859 --> 01:24:37,646
[GROSSI]: producers of rare earths or cutting-edge technologies that are already organized.

741
01:24:38,046 --> 01:24:46,294
[GROSSI]: I think we have to be prudent in this area to make sure that we strike the right balance.

742
01:24:47,375 --> 01:25:00,796
[GROSSI]: between having the dynamism that is going to be helping economies, is going to be helping education, innovation and so forth.

743
01:25:02,238 --> 01:25:13,224
[GROSSI]: at the same time avoiding excesses and the absence of the human in the loop factor, which is at the end of the day what we need.

744
01:25:15,245 --> 01:25:25,590
[GROSSI]: Some people have referred to even the possibility of having an IEA for AI, which may sound flattering, but I don't agree.

745
01:25:26,250 --> 01:25:28,151
[GROSSI]: contrary to what people may believe.

746
01:25:28,171 --> 01:25:42,377
[GROSSI]: I think the algorithmic dimension is rather different from an area where you have nuclear material accountability and facilities that can be inspected.

747
01:25:42,397 --> 01:25:51,241
[GROSSI]: We have to be, I think, prudent in believing that we can have systems of control that are really effective.

748
01:25:51,341 --> 01:25:52,522
[GROSSI]: Having an illusion

749
01:25:53,222 --> 01:25:57,226
[GROSSI]: of verification is worse than having none at all.

750
01:25:57,847 --> 01:25:58,528
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

751
01:25:58,768 --> 01:26:00,770
[SPEAKER_10]: Now I'm just going to move on to the last two questions.

752
01:26:00,790 --> 01:26:02,191
[SPEAKER_10]: They're both from Siu Yongs.

753
01:26:02,392 --> 01:26:09,839
[SPEAKER_10]: So we have Siu Yong Choi, undergraduate student, Jeju National University, and Siu Yong Yang, undergraduate student from Jeju National University.

754
01:26:10,059 --> 01:26:14,844
[SPEAKER_10]: If you can both identify yourself, let's start with Siu Yong Choi first.

755
01:26:14,904 --> 01:26:15,285
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

756
01:26:15,816 --> 01:26:17,797
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, thank you for the introduction.

757
01:26:17,817 --> 01:26:19,558
[SPEAKER_16]: It's a pleasure to be here.

758
01:26:20,158 --> 01:26:34,405
[SPEAKER_16]: My question is among the many global challenges we face today and what do you think is the most overlooked issues that young people should pay more attention to?

759
01:26:34,745 --> 01:26:35,185
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

760
01:26:35,525 --> 01:26:36,525
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, Siu-Yong Choi.

761
01:26:36,566 --> 01:26:41,588
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's get the question from Siu-Yong Yan, who is also here, and that's about the SDGs.

762
01:26:41,608 --> 01:26:42,388
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's hear that question.

763
01:26:42,408 --> 01:26:46,190
[SPEAKER_10]: We'll take both those questions and then, of course, finally conclude with your responses.

764
01:26:47,570 --> 01:26:49,131
[SPEAKER_10]: Siu-Yong Yang, are you here?

765
01:26:49,271 --> 01:26:49,851
[SPEAKER_10]: Ah, there you are.

766
01:26:50,932 --> 01:26:51,272
[SPEAKER_10]: Go ahead.

767
01:26:54,068 --> 01:27:05,498
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, Mr. Micusel already got the similar question, but as the SDGs are set to conclude in 2030, I'm curious about your vision for the future.

768
01:27:06,079 --> 01:27:13,766
[SPEAKER_01]: So my question is, what values do you believe should guide the next generation of the global development agenda?

769
01:27:14,285 --> 01:27:26,098
[SPEAKER_01]: And if you could give a name to the post 2030 development goals like MDGs or SDGs, what would it be and what do you think should be the most important priority?

770
01:27:27,150 --> 01:27:28,571
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you to both this year youngs.

771
01:27:28,611 --> 01:27:29,432
[SPEAKER_10]: Who would like to respond?

772
01:27:29,472 --> 01:27:30,272
[SPEAKER_10]: There are two questions.

773
01:27:30,453 --> 01:27:34,636
[SPEAKER_10]: One about the issues that have been overlooked that the young generation should pay attention to.

774
01:27:34,956 --> 01:27:39,680
[SPEAKER_10]: And the second one, what's going to succeed the Sustainable Development Goals?

775
01:27:40,680 --> 01:27:46,845
[SPEAKER_10]: Rebecca, I believe you put up, and Marcel and Maria, and let's do it quickly so we can get to our concluding statements.

776
01:27:46,945 --> 01:27:47,306
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

777
01:27:48,006 --> 01:28:02,384
[GRYNSPAN]: Let me take the second question and say that I think that the MDGs and the SDGs have been very important, but let's remember that the date of 2030 is arbitrary.

778
01:28:02,985 --> 01:28:10,690
[GRYNSPAN]: And if we look at the SDGs, only 18% is in track to be complied by 2030.

779
01:28:11,070 --> 01:28:13,812
[GRYNSPAN]: So the agenda won't be finished by 2030.

780
01:28:14,733 --> 01:28:17,595
[GRYNSPAN]: So I think that the priority

781
01:28:18,135 --> 01:28:33,794
[GRYNSPAN]: has to be to support countries that want to continue with the SDGs because they have not been a reality in their countries yet to be able to comply, to implement the agenda that continues to be an important agenda.

782
01:28:34,435 --> 01:28:39,578
[GRYNSPAN]: And my second point is that we have to go beyond GDP.

783
01:28:40,179 --> 01:28:43,981
[GRYNSPAN]: So it's a matter also of how we measure development.

784
01:28:44,081 --> 01:28:49,325
[GRYNSPAN]: And I am an economist, so it's rare for an economist to say GDP doesn't tell you the story.

785
01:28:49,905 --> 01:28:57,868
[GRYNSPAN]: we have to measure well development so we can take the right policy decisions that will benefit people.

786
01:28:58,068 --> 01:28:59,569
[GRYNSPAN]: So these are my two points.

787
01:28:59,769 --> 01:29:00,770
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for those two points.

788
01:29:00,830 --> 01:29:02,110
[SPEAKER_10]: I've just been informed.

789
01:29:02,130 --> 01:29:03,291
[SPEAKER_10]: We've only got three minutes left.

790
01:29:03,351 --> 01:29:06,892
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm sorry, I thought we had extended the session, but we only have three minutes.

791
01:29:06,912 --> 01:29:13,355
[SPEAKER_10]: So let's just get another quick response from, I believe, Macky Sal, and then I'm going to start with the concluding sentiments at the end.

792
01:29:14,035 --> 01:29:14,235
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

793
01:29:14,976 --> 01:29:15,436
[SPEAKER_10]: Very good.

794
01:29:16,968 --> 01:29:17,548
[SALL]: Very well.

795
01:29:19,730 --> 01:29:37,059
[SALL]: So regarding the questions about the overlooked issues that young people should pay more attention to, I think not only the young people but also the governments, the public powers, and the universal organization that is the United Nations.

796
01:29:37,399 --> 01:29:50,827
[SALL]: I believe that the issue of education is a fundamental issue, which is a transcendental issue, and it allows us to comprehend the entire issue of artificial intelligence.

797
01:29:51,187 --> 01:29:54,229
[SALL]: We knew the digital divide at the beginning of the year 2000.

798
01:29:55,890 --> 01:30:05,597
[SALL]: Nowadays, because we had a paradigm shift regarding education, Asian countries are showing us the way.

799
01:30:05,977 --> 01:30:15,924
[SALL]: After the Second World War, all the Asian countries changed the paradigm in their education, which made them able to become developed countries.

800
01:30:16,704 --> 01:30:24,870
[SALL]: And that is why those challenges of education will ensure the future of the younger generation to give jobs and to give

801
01:30:25,330 --> 01:30:26,330
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, merci.

802
01:30:26,370 --> 01:30:29,151
[SPEAKER_10]: That's right, education and of course Asia leading the way there.

803
01:30:29,551 --> 01:30:39,954
[SPEAKER_10]: Now we have concluding statements and I should say that there was a lottery draw that was conducted before our session here on stage so that you could all have your concluding statements.

804
01:30:40,354 --> 01:30:41,955
[SPEAKER_10]: They were meant to be 90 seconds.

805
01:30:42,095 --> 01:30:43,615
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't know if we've got 90 seconds.

806
01:30:43,655 --> 01:30:47,296
[SPEAKER_10]: Do we have 90 seconds for each individual for their concluding statements still?

807
01:30:48,694 --> 01:30:49,334
[SPEAKER_10]: I hope we do.

808
01:30:49,354 --> 01:30:51,155
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, so let's start.

809
01:30:51,736 --> 01:30:55,077
[SPEAKER_10]: The draw was won first speaker, Rebecca.

810
01:30:55,418 --> 01:30:56,758
[SPEAKER_10]: So let's go with you, Rebecca.

811
01:30:57,799 --> 01:30:58,139
[GRYNSPAN]: Thank you.

812
01:30:59,896 --> 01:31:27,932
[GRYNSPAN]: Well, I have to say that I am running because I care, because I think we can be better, because I believe in the principles and the charter of the UN, because I think I am the best candidate, and because the story of my family have taught me what war takes away from you and what peace can give you back.

813
01:31:29,033 --> 01:31:35,281
[GRYNSPAN]: So my life and the story of my life has gone through these three pillars of the UN.

814
01:31:35,582 --> 01:31:42,991
[GRYNSPAN]: I wouldn't be here if I didn't believe on peace, on development, and in human rights.

815
01:31:43,251 --> 01:31:45,154
[GRYNSPAN]: That's the story of my family.

816
01:31:45,214 --> 01:31:47,236
[GRYNSPAN]: That's the story of myself.

817
01:31:47,817 --> 01:31:48,798
[GRYNSPAN]: I've been in government.

818
01:31:49,398 --> 01:31:55,122
[GRYNSPAN]: I've been the coordinator of the social and economic sectors in my country.

819
01:31:56,043 --> 01:32:03,648
[GRYNSPAN]: I know what it is to take decisions under pressure in very difficult circumstances with a lot of financial constraints.

820
01:32:04,348 --> 01:32:07,170
[GRYNSPAN]: So I want to do that for the UN.

821
01:32:07,550 --> 01:32:10,953
[GRYNSPAN]: I think I can really drive the UN to be better.

822
01:32:11,673 --> 01:32:29,361
[GRYNSPAN]: to be relevant, to do, to refocus, to be successful, and that I can bridge between countries and people to reach the consensus and the trust needed for that to happen.

823
01:32:29,941 --> 01:32:31,042
[GRYNSPAN]: Thank you.

824
01:32:31,762 --> 01:32:35,685
[GRYNSPAN]: skepticism is okay, fatalism is not acceptable.

825
01:32:36,165 --> 01:32:40,168
[GRYNSPAN]: We have to have hope in the future and I think that I can do that.

826
01:32:40,508 --> 01:32:41,749
[SPEAKER_10]: Great concluding statement.

827
01:32:41,849 --> 01:32:42,650
[SPEAKER_10]: Next up, Maria.

828
01:32:43,690 --> 01:32:49,434
[ESPINOSA]: Well, I am running for the position of Secretary General because I believe in the UN.

829
01:32:50,275 --> 01:32:56,960
[ESPINOSA]: I think the UN continues to be the best institutional creation of humankind.

830
01:32:58,142 --> 01:33:06,148
[ESPINOSA]: It is a human-made organization, so I'm a strong believer that manifest destiny for the UN not working.

831
01:33:06,268 --> 01:33:07,469
[ESPINOSA]: We cannot accept that.

832
01:33:09,230 --> 01:33:13,233
[ESPINOSA]: I also believe in a phrase that a Nobel laureate said,

833
01:33:13,813 --> 01:33:20,680
[ESPINOSA]: The opposite of love is not hate, it is indifference, is because I don't want to be indifferent.

834
01:33:21,141 --> 01:33:33,213
[ESPINOSA]: I think I can contribute to make the UN better, more efficient, leaner, more service-oriented, and to really touch and transform the lives of people on the ground.

835
01:33:34,574 --> 01:33:37,716
[ESPINOSA]: The leader that the UN needs is a Renaissance leader.

836
01:33:38,336 --> 01:33:47,460
[ESPINOSA]: It's a person that understands development, that has worked on the peace and security field, that is committed to the human rights agenda.

837
01:33:47,900 --> 01:33:50,041
[ESPINOSA]: My entire career shows that.

838
01:33:50,542 --> 01:33:52,162
[ESPINOSA]: The ability to bring

839
01:33:53,543 --> 01:33:59,728
[ESPINOSA]: the peace and security pillar together with the development and together with the human rights pillar.

840
01:34:00,028 --> 01:34:20,363
[ESPINOSA]: Being a minister of defense, a foreign minister, being a minister of culture and natural heritage, ambassador in New York, ambassador in Geneva, president of the UN General Assembly, I think provides the credentials for me to serve the organization to make it better and to make it more connected to the people it serves.

841
01:34:20,743 --> 01:34:21,244
[SPEAKER_10]: Well said.

842
01:34:21,284 --> 01:34:21,904
[ESPINOSA]: Thank you, Maria.

843
01:34:23,450 --> 01:34:23,870
[RODRIGUES]: Thank you.

844
01:34:24,671 --> 01:34:33,656
[RODRIGUES]: 80 years after the formation of the UN and the opportunity to reflect, I believe that the UN has delivered and continues to deliver.

845
01:34:34,157 --> 01:34:42,342
[RODRIGUES]: The Charter remains as relevant as it was in 1945 as the standard for stability and for hope for future generations.

846
01:34:42,802 --> 01:34:47,225
[RODRIGUES]: But we have big challenges and the UN must change, the UN must adapt.

847
01:34:48,170 --> 01:34:51,234
[RODRIGUES]: and we should be able to do this together.

848
01:34:51,854 --> 01:35:03,367
[RODRIGUES]: And so I believe that this Jeju forum should reignite our march for peace and prosperity and that together we must remake a UN that is

849
01:35:04,188 --> 01:35:08,549
[RODRIGUES]: that learns from its past, that is fit for today, and that is ready for the future.

850
01:35:09,010 --> 01:35:30,537
[RODRIGUES]: And I'm running because I believe that my experience as a Minister of Foreign Affairs, a Minister of Indigenous Peoples Affairs, an international civil servant with the UN, and now a permanent representative walking the halls of the UN and in the negotiation room for the last five and a half years, that I can run this race together with you and we could make a better UN.

851
01:35:32,437 --> 01:35:35,900
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you very much.

852
01:35:36,220 --> 01:35:41,944
[SALL]: I can say after my skills, I'm not running for a career.

853
01:35:42,704 --> 01:35:55,293
[SALL]: I'm running for impact as former head of state, 12 years in my country, leading also AU and working

854
01:35:56,345 --> 01:36:13,202
[SALL]: individually with all leaders of the G20 and getting the position of Africa as a permanent member of G20 shows me it is possible to rebuild trust with UN.

855
01:36:17,532 --> 01:36:41,539
[SALL]: is that my engagement as a leader, as a politicist man, is that in Africa in general there are lots of conflicts and I can still serve the peoples from the United Nations with the purpose of making a stronger

856
01:36:44,085 --> 01:37:04,398
[SALL]: a more resilient organization, a reformed organization, especially with the trust that we need to rebuild the trust among the member states and, of course, the trust and dialogue that must rebuild among the permanent members of the Security Council.

857
01:37:04,738 --> 01:37:09,321
[SALL]: I believe that is the participation and contribution that I can bring to the table.

858
01:37:10,997 --> 01:37:11,478
[SPEAKER_10]: Merci.

859
01:37:11,638 --> 01:37:13,680
[SPEAKER_10]: And concluding remarks, finally, Rafael.

860
01:37:13,820 --> 01:37:15,742
[GROSSI]: Thank you very much.

861
01:37:16,462 --> 01:37:30,436
[GROSSI]: This election or selection, in my opinion, is arguably one of the most consequential ones we have had in the history of the United Nations.

862
01:37:31,337 --> 01:37:53,268
[GROSSI]: Everything we have discussed, everything we have heard today only confirm that in this world fragmented, as the title of the conference says, with the perhaps for the first time situation where the UN in itself is being questioned

863
01:37:54,128 --> 01:38:07,477
[GROSSI]: the institution is being put between brackets, its future is in doubt, then the choice of the person

864
01:38:09,142 --> 01:38:19,888
[GROSSI]: who is going to be leading this organization over the next few years becomes a dramatic choice for all of us.

865
01:38:22,029 --> 01:38:33,836
[GROSSI]: It's not because the UN is there and there is a charter and the charter is a timeless piece for all of us that the UN is going to be called to fulfill its role.

866
01:38:34,657 --> 01:38:36,618
[GROSSI]: It's when the UN can add

867
01:38:37,327 --> 01:38:41,351
[GROSSI]: value is when the UN can solve problems, that we are going to see that.

868
01:38:41,831 --> 01:38:49,718
[GROSSI]: And I've seen that personally in the battlefields of the war, protecting a nuclear power plant from a disaster.

869
01:38:50,218 --> 01:38:57,885
[GROSSI]: We have seen it now when we are trying to solve one of the most intractable conflicts around the nuclear

870
01:38:58,876 --> 01:39:01,238
[GROSSI]: programme of a country in the Middle East.

871
01:39:01,638 --> 01:39:06,302
[GROSSI]: The multilateral institution is needed at that time.

872
01:39:06,742 --> 01:39:10,445
[GROSSI]: So, a moment of choice and let's make the right decision.

873
01:39:11,184 --> 01:39:12,324
[SPEAKER_10]: And the time is up.

874
01:39:12,484 --> 01:39:13,044
[SPEAKER_10]: Wow.

875
01:39:13,124 --> 01:39:18,385
[SPEAKER_10]: We have heard from the five candidates who are here with us here in Jeju.

876
01:39:18,485 --> 01:39:21,626
[SPEAKER_10]: It was always going to be a struggle to keep you all on time.

877
01:39:21,946 --> 01:39:34,709
[SPEAKER_10]: I have to say we're only 10 minutes over, but thank you all and best of luck to all six of the candidates who are vying for this very crucial role as the next Secretary General of the United Nations.

878
01:39:34,949 --> 01:39:40,630
[SPEAKER_10]: As we heard from Ban Ki-moon himself, he doesn't envy you, but I'm sure you'll all do as

879
01:39:41,733 --> 01:39:41,974
[SPEAKER_10]: job.

880
01:39:42,396 --> 01:39:44,806
[SPEAKER_10]: Once again, a big round of applause to our candidates, please.

881
01:40:22,527 --> 01:40:26,208
The world is no longer connected.

882
01:40:26,368 --> 01:40:29,569
We are moving in different directions.

883
01:40:47,480 --> 01:40:49,466
[SPEAKER_06]: How far and fast can this actually go?

884
01:40:49,546 --> 01:40:50,509
[SPEAKER_06]: No more declarations.

885
01:40:50,529 --> 01:40:52,596
[SPEAKER_06]: We need to turn these promises into reality.

886
01:40:52,616 --> 01:40:53,659
[SPEAKER_01]: It's breaking apart!

